snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protest turns violent in London
snippet.description:
(1 Jun 2020) Clashes erupted in central London on Sunday after a largely peaceful Black Lives Matter protest.
Tension escalated as police tried to clear a junction in Parliament Square blocked by protesters.
The demonstrators were rallying against the death of George Floyd, who died in Minnesota on May 25 after a police officer pressed his knee on his neck, which had a sparked a week of demonstrations in the US.
A number of people were seen being arrested and put into police vans, the Metropolitan Police Service said late Sunday 23 people had been arrested in relation to the protests.
One protester, who chose to remain nameless, said the demonstrators had been protesting peacefully and criticised the actions of the police.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | children's books |
snippet.description:
Today, I share six children's books with you, that enforce the Black Lives Matter movement and educate children about race. These children's books spread the BLACK LIVES MATTER message and that racism should not be accepted. EVER. Children should learn from a young age to not discriminate against people because of the colour of their skin and it saddens me that racism and inequality is ever present in our society and all over the world. I hope that these books are used more and more in schools and in homes to show children that racism is of the past and should not exist in today's society. Something must be done. SOON!

I encourage parents, carers, teachers to use these books to open up discussions about race and racism with children.

Please educate yourself and others, read these books, read websites, make donations, sign petitions, speak up at protests. George Floyd didn't deserve what happened to him, no innocent man or woman deserves that, black lives matter.

Here's some useful links that you can use:
https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/#
^^tells you all the different things you can do

donate any spare money: https://blacklivesmatter.com
or
https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd\

sign: https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-...

there's so many available resources online so please do loads of research, thank you for watching.

LINKS TO THE BOOKS I SPOKE ABOUT!

My hair is beautiful by Shauntay Grant: https://amzn.to/2My9127
Sulwe by Lupita Nyong'o: https://amzn.to/2zewsui
Little leaders - Bold women in black history by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3760bSy
Dream big little one by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3cCIIT2
We march by Shane. W. Evans: https://amzn.to/375YVic
Race cars by Jenny Devenny: https://amzn.to/2Uj90mT
Something happened in our town by Ann Hazzard, Marianne Celano, and Marietta Collins: https://amzn.to/3dGez6A

Intro song: Joakim Karud - By The Croft

These books are aimed for primary aged children up to and including adults. Please donate any spare change to black lives matter. Thank you so much for watching and reading this.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter OKC issues demands
snippet.description:
Rev. T. Sheri Dickerson, executive director of the Black Lives Matter OKC chapter, holds a press conference outside the city hall building in downtown Oklahoma City. Dickerson issued the group's following demands:

● An apology from Police Chief Wade Gourley and Mayor David Holt and the immediate resignation of Gourley, whose lack of leadership resulted in aggressive actions by the police towards peaceful protesters, escalating tensions and resulting in violence that could have been avoided.
● The immediate release without charges of all incarcerated protestors who were arrested for nonviolent offenses or “resisting arrest” while defending themselves or their loved ones from unlawful use of excessive force by OKC PD and the sheriff.
● Disciplinary action and termination be taken against all police officers who violently attacked peaceful protesters.
● The immediate installation of an independent citizens’ complaint review board for the OKC PD, which will have authority to review all complaints, including use of force, and discipline offending officers.
● Mayor Holt meet with us within 24 hours.
● Provision of training in de-escalation tactics for all OCPD officers, which must include training in interactions with persons who have mental health issues as well as training that includes cultural sensitivity.
● The immediate public release of the arrest record of Olain Jefferson, Jr. and body cam footage of all police involved in his arrest.
● The immediate public release of all video footage of the OKCPD incident involving and resulting in the death of Derrick Ollie Sr.
● The arrest and prosecution of David Stewart for the kidnapping and illegal confinement of Mr. Travis Miller Sr.
● Justice for the family of Mr. Elray Barber who was shot and killed by OKCPD on Christmas Eve 2019.
● Justice for Ms. Rolana Keeler who was shot by OKCPD on Christmas Eve 2019 while unarmed.
● Mayor Holt commit to the construction of a grocery store on the Eastside of OKC to be completed within 6 months.
● The granting of clemency and immediate release of wrongfully charged member of our community, Julius Jones, by Governor Stitt.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter to Me - a Jewish Response to Racial Injustice
snippet.description:
If you are Black, your life matters to me. Today I wanted to share a Jewish perspective on why the #BlackLivesMatter movement is so important to me and my thoughts on racism and injustice. The world we live in is fractured but it is our greatest responsibility to repair it.⁣ In the Torah we read, ⁣Tzedek tzedek tirdof⁣ תרדף צדק ‎צדק ⁣Justice, justice you shall pursue.⁣ As a #Jewish person, as a mother, as an American - your life matters to me. 

SUBSCRIBE for MORE Jewish Mom Content: https://goo.gl/4t88MD 
FOLLOW along on INSTAGRAM www.instagram.com/myjewishmommylife

Proceeds from this video will be donated to the NAACP: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/naacp-1

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter is how we end the divide and rule crisis of Covid-19 -- Untitled UK: 2 June (E17)
snippet.description:
Architectural journalist discusses how the death of George Floyd exposes the massive inqualities caused by divide and rule politics in the USA and elsewhere. 



This episode discusses how the Black Lives Matter campaign offers everyone an opportunity to work together to overthrow the dominance of divide and rule politics, and creater a fairer, safer and healthier society for everyone. 



It looks at new research by Public Health England showing how BAME people are much more at risk of death of Covid-19 than white people and discusses the likely impact of health inequalities on these findings. 



The show also looks at recent remarks by former UK prime minister Gordon Brown calling for a united global response to the crisis and a crackdown on the trillions of dollars of wealth hidden in tax havens. 

Thanks for watching and please share your comments!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter...
snippet.description:
R.I.P to everyone who battled with racism 

Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international activist movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

Police killed at least 104 unarmed black people in 2015, nearly twice each week. (See which police departments were responsible for these deaths)

Nearly 1 in 3 black people killed by police in 2015 were identified as unarmed, though the actual number is likely higher due to underreporting

36% of unarmed people killed by police were black in 2015 despite black people being only 13% of the U.S. population

Unarmed black people were killed at 5x the rate of unarmed whites in 2015

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Vancouver Protest 2020 | Anti Racism Rally
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter 
Hundreds gathered outside the Vancouver Art Gallery Sunday afternoon for a protest demanding justice following George Floyd’s death at the hands of Minneapolis police this week.

This is the latest Vancouver Protest 2020 which shows Anti Racism Rally. 

Protesters wore masks to prevent coronavirus spread and brought signs bearing messages such as “Black lives matter,” “silence=compliance,” and “I can’t breathe,” the latter referencing Floyd’s last words as a police officer knelt on his neck for several minutes before he died. 

There was a moment of silence held at the demonstration to honour Floyd and other victims of police brutality before speeches and calls to action. Organizers plan to have the rally stay in Robson Square and not go on a march downtown, partly to avoid coronavirus spread and partly to avoid conflict with commuters and potential anti-protesters. 

The officer who held his knee to Floyd’s neck has now been charged with third degree murder and manslaughter. But Callendar-Prasad and other demonstrators want the other officers present at the time to be charged as well.

“This is the time to fight. This is the time to unite. No matter your skin colour, your pigment, where you’re from, this is something you should care about,” they said in an Instagram video preparing for the demonstration.

#BlackLivesMatter #BLM #VancouverProtest #GeorgeFloyd #AntiRacism #protest2020 #NVAliveDiaries

snippet.title: What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"? | Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"?   ABC10 anchor Chris Thomas explains.
Follow Chris at https://www.facebook.com/ChrisThomasNews/

There have been protests, demonstrations, and riots over George Floyd's death for the past week. Well, that's the assumption, at least. In the 90s, 15-year-old Latasha Harlins was shot in the back of the head when she turned her back to a fight that broke out in a store. The Korean grocer who shot her was given a suspended sentence, probation, and a fine. Shortly after, the four officers that brutally beat Rodney King were found not guilty! 

These two events led to an explosion (the LA riots) of rage based on the recent examples that black lives don't matter. On February 23rd, 2020, Ahmaud Arbery was jogging when a pickup truck blocked his path. Two people were inside; one jumped out with a gun and shot Arbery. Oh, by the way, this was filmed by another participant in the attack. It was not until May 7th that the McMichaels were arrested. This arrest did not happen until public outrage spread across social media when the video was released on May 5th. Why the outrage? Well, the life of Ahmaud Arbery didn't matter enough to those in power to have the McMichaels arrested immediately for Arbery's death instead of waiting for more than two months. 

By now, you've all seen the video of the officer pressing his knee on the neck of George Floyd. If you watched the video, you heard him begging for the opportunity to breathe. A request that sounds sadly similar to Eric Garner. For over five minutes, officer Derek Chauvin and the other officers ignored Floyd's requests to breathe. 

These two events, like the two events in the 90s, have led to an explosion of outrage in the form of protests, demonstrations, and riots. Why? Because many Americans now understand why it is necessary to say, Black Lives Matter.

A request that sounds sadly similar to Eric Garner. For over five minutes, officer Derek Chauvin and the other officers ignored Floyd's requests to breathe. 

These two events, like the two events in the 90s, have led to an explosion of outrage in the form of protests, demonstrations, and riots. Why? Because many Americans now understand why it is necessary to say, Black Lives Matter.

snippet.title: YES, SHOW SOLIDARITY WITH BLACK LIVES MATTER BUT ALSO INTEGRATE IT WITH THE CLASS STRUGGLE TOO
snippet.description:
As pointed out by the Black Panther Party "We don't care what anybody says. We don't think to fight fire with fire. We think to fight fire with water. We're going to fight racism, not with racism but we're going to fight it with solidarity. We say we're not going to fight Capitalism with Black Capitalism, but we're going to fight it with Socialism." 

Identity politics in itself is a very complicated subject when it comes to Marxist-Leninist theory because while there are a lot of differences between identity politics and class politics, there are also a lot of overlaps too.

--- SOME GOOD RESOURCES ---

America Never Stood For Freedom - Hakim: https://youtu.be/-HflHrHvYsw 

US: What Is To Be Done? - Hakim: https://youtu.be/f68HZ0hEqeY 

New Communist Parties Ditching Identity Politics - Jason Unruhe: https://youtu.be/kSmfrH8hjLw 

Yes, Identity Politics Divides The Left - Jason Unruhe: https://youtu.be/iEZcBbdgMU8 

Some Thoughts On Identity Politics - TheFinnishBolshevik: https://youtu.be/G9PyFR3Dr8I

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Modesto March
snippet.description:
More than 1,000  protesters marched through the streets of Modesto for more than seven miles on May 31, 2020 to protest the death of George Floyd and police brutality throughout the nation. After hours of peaceful protest, the march was marred with violence when agitators clashed with police along J Street.

Filmed and Edited: Frankie Tovar
#ModestoProtest #GeorgeFloyd #BLMProtesters

snippet.title: Never Enough - The Greatest Showman | black lives matter remix
snippet.description:
This week for #musicmonday is for the culture. Too many of us are dying unjustly. We need to pray. We need to donate. We need to buy black. We need to support people in office that want to bring justice. We need to stand together. This was the only way I could think to express how I feel about recent events. No more silence. It’s time for action #blm #blacklivesmatter #greatestshowman #parody #remix

Lyrics 

I can no longer hold my breath
Can’t let it stay this way
Injustice needs to end
MLK said, “Dream with me”
But racism is louder now
Can you feel it echoing?
Raise your hand
Will you stand here with me?
Don’t wanna do this without you

Coverage of a thousand protests
And a hashtag that gets you noticed
Will never be enough
Never be enough
Four police fired is still too little
These hands are sick and tired and it’ll
Never be enough 
Never be enough

Til we’re free
Never, never
Never, never
Never, I just want
To be free
Never enough
Never enough
Never enough
Please don’t 
Kill me
I can’t breath 

Unarmed kings and queens are dying
As soon as we wake up we’re fighting
This trauma is too much
But still to hope I clutch 
Allies speak up but it’s still too little 
I raise my hands and kneel but it’ll
Never be enough
When will we be enough 

To be free
Give them pressure
Show displeasure
Let me be free, can’t you see
Is this enough 
We try to be tough
But we just want
To be free
Can’t you see
Don’t kill me
I can’t breath

Will never be enough

Never be enough

Never, never

Never enough
Never enough
Never enough
Please don’t 
Kill me

As soon as we wake up we’re fighting
This trauma is too much

I raise my hands and kneel but it’ll
Never be enough

To be free
Give them pressure

To be free

snippet.title: Rioters Burn Down Minneapolis, Because 'Black Lives Matter'...But No One Else's Does
snippet.description: So Minneapolis is on fire. Because as we all know by now, the best response to a black man being killed by the cops is to steal a big screen TV and burn down the local liquor store. It’s been nearly 6 years since Black Lives Matter got its start in the streets of Ferguson, Missouri. Six years, and they still can’t get their heads out of their own rear ends long enough to be marginally decent, let alone credible.

snippet.title: Moving Protest Art: #JUSTICEFORGEORGE #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
George Floyd was murdered on May 25th 2020 by a Police Officer named Derek Chauvin. Chauvin knelt on Floyd's neck for 7 minutes despite Floyd begging with him saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "I'm about to die."

This tragedy has sparked protests and riots for #BlackLivesMatter not only in the US but now across the globe as people stand up against police brutality and institutionalised racism.

To those who criticise the #BlackLivesMatter movement: 
#Equality is a cause everyone should fight for. 
Whether it be through protests, fundraising, donations, petitions, music, art or film, we must do what we can to make people hear and make people see. No Justice, No Peace.

This artwork is the least I can do to continue to spread the message that we will not stand for inequality any longer, that we refuse to see human beings suffer.

"I understand that I will never be able to understand completely. But I stand with you and I will not let you do this alone. You were never meant to."

Thank you to the wonderful Dan Pacini for allowing me to use his new song, 'The Ballad of George Floyd' in this video. Dan is a good friend, a talented musician and dedicated activist and you can find more music from him and his band here: 
https://soundcloud.com/the-hypothetics 
https://instagram.com/danncheesemusic?igshid=1ed62iwww10a3

If you would like to see more of my work please subscribe to my YouTube Channel and check out my social media links:
Facebook (Art and Photography): https://www.facebook.com/RhiannonDavisVisualArt/
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/_rhiannondavis.visualart/
Twitter: https://twitter.com/_rhiannondavis

#BlackLivesMatter #JusticeForGeorge #Activism

snippet.title: Raleigh Black Lives Matter Protest 5/31
snippet.description:
A montage of the Raleigh protest.

The last scene is the riot officers starting to march in. There were a 5 men trying to take over the protest and start a riot. One of them told me he wasn't even there for the protest, just to mess with people. The other 4 had baseball bats, they were escorted away from the protest, and they made their way back when the police came with tear gas

You have to separate the two. There are angry people being manipulated into becoming rioters. Their anger is justified. But we can't ignore the opportunists. They must be stopped

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter March Bristol, England June 7th 2020
snippet.description:
A glimpse into the Black Lives Matter march in Bristol, England on June 7th 2020. Thousands of people gathered at College Green to make a stand against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police in Minnesota, and the continued institutionalised oppression and dehumanization of black people. 

The march culminated with the toppling of the statue of Edward Colston, a 17th century slave trader, which was subsequently dragged along the Harbourside and tossed into the river. 

Sadly I missed the destruction of the statue…

Speakers:
Daniel Edmund https://twitter.com/Daniel_Edmund
Nasra Ayub https://twitter.com/nasra_ayub

Donate, sign petitions and keep up to date with global actions at:
https://blacklivesmatter.com/

A film by Arthur Cauty

Shot on Panasonic S1H with Canon 24-105 f/4 L lens

snippet.title: John Boyega makes impassioned speech at Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
John Boyega has issued an emotional rallying cry in support of Black Lives Matter in London's Hyde Park. 'I need you to understand how painful it is to be reminded every day that your race means nothing,' the Star Wars actor said. 'Black lives have always mattered.' Boyega's speech was widely shared on social media after video was posted by SB.TV and others

snippet.title: The History of the #BlackLivesMatter Movement What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? BLM Explained
snippet.description:
The History Behind the #BlackLivesMatter Movement | What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? | BLM - This is a special video summarizing the events that have led to the creation and influence of the #blacklivesmatter movement. It covers how the #BlackLivesMatter BLM movement got started, and who started it. It lists the goals and problems that are being faced by the BLM. It lists several dozen names of people who have been killed by racial injustice and police brutality. It covers different protests around the United States of America, including involvements from athletes within the NBA and the NFL. Lastly, it mentions the most recent events of George Floyd's death in Minneapolis, Minnesota and the recent call for the acknowledgement and accountability of the police and the affirmation of the prosperity of black lives.

#BlackLivesMatter #GeorgeFloyd #BlackLifeMatters

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - are the stats accurate? | Professor Wilfred Reilly
snippet.description:
The US (as well as large parts of the western world) has been gripped by protests in the wake of the appalling killing of George Floyd by american police. The black lives matter movement is central to the protests, but are the claims it makes accurate? I spoke to author and academic Wilfred Reilly about this. His argument is that the majority of the black lives matter movement's central assertions are inaccurate or misleading.

I understand that this is a highly contentious and emotive topic so please feel free to leave a comment letting us know if your thoughts (but try to keep them civil if possible).

Please give the video a LIKE AND SUBSCRIBE, thanks! Also remember to LEAVE US A COMMENT letting us know what you think.

snippet.title: The Math of Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
If we want to move the conversation on policing & race forward, we have to do math correctly. For years I’ve watched countless (literally they can’t count) news anchors and political commentators brutalize numbers when discussing police brutality. And by not making this video until now, I was part of the problem. After a lot of research, I recommend that you don’t take stats like these for granted, that you look into them yourselves. Hope you find this helpful, and at the very least, a tool to disarm any BS math used to protect a 100% real systemic bias.
 
Created by myself & Chai Sharma
Edited by Daniel Valencia
Contributions by Diana Ishimizu, Ryan Sudhakran, Christopher Thomas, and Amanda Justice   

#sammyobeid #blacklivesmatter #police

Sources:

https://www.statista.com/statistics/585152/people-shot-to-death-by-us-police-by-race/
https://www.prisonpolicy.org/scans/ccj/African%20American%20Males.pdf
https://www.sentencingproject.org/publications/un-report-on-racial-disparities/
https://research.msu.edu/innocent-african-americans-more-likely-to-be-wrongfully-convicted/
https://www.odmp.org
https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s/2018/crime-in-the-u.s.-2018/tables/expanded-homicide-data-table-3.xls
https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/08/study-claims-white-police-no-more-likely-shoot-minorities-draws-fire
https://datausa.io/profile/soc/police-officers
https://www.vox.com/2020/5/31/21276004/anger-police-killing-george-floyd-protests
https://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&iid=5259

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest: This Is Tulsa: Part II
snippet.description:
#BlackLivesMatter #Tulsa #Protest

Do you know what makes Tulsa such an amazing city? It's the people who live here. To have such an outspoken and diverse community of citizens who want the best for their city and ALL the people who live here, and are willing to be active and vocal about those desires through peaceful protest.

Part of the reason it's important to document what's happening at these protests is to reinforce the fact that these are peaceful protests and not to let the narrative get co-opted by those who would use the opportunity for their own agendas.

snippet.title: Black lives matter demonstrators. USA. I can’t breathe. George Floyd. Justice.
snippet.description:
Пожалуйста, покончите с расизмом и стереотипам.  Мусульмане не являются террористами. Азиаты не вирус. Мексиканцы не являются незаконными. Афроамериканцы не угроза. Коренные американцы не дикари. все мы люди одной природы, и следует подчеркнуть, что мы похожи. глобализация не должна была привести к этому. Глобализация предназначена для того, чтобы люди ассимилировали и приняли другие культуры и нации и находили радость в каждой а не зажигать протесты и разрушат всё от расизма. 

Please end racism and white supremacy. Muslims are NOT terrorists. Asians are NOT a virus. Mexicans are NOT illegal. African Americans are NOT a threat. Native Americans are NOT savages. We are all HUMANS of the same nature and it should be emphasized that we are similar. Globalization wasn’t supposed to result to this. It was meant for people to assimilate and accept other cultures and nations and find joy in each, not spark protests and destruction from racism. 
#blacklivesmatter #icantbreathe #justiceforgeorgefloyd #notoracism #stopracism #stopkilling #stopstereotypes #peacetotheworld

snippet.title: LIVE: Black Lives Matter-demonstratie in Den Haag
snippet.description:
In Den Haag zijn honderden mensen samengekomen om te demonstreren tegen racisme en politiegeweld. De deelnemers van de Black Lives Matter-demonstratie dragen mondkapjes en houden afstand van elkaar. 

NOS-verslaggever Hasan Coşkun vroeg ze waarom zij het belangrijk vinden om op het Malieveld te staan. Ook vraagt hij hoe zij hebben gekeken naar het protest op de Dam, waar geen afstand werd gehouden.

#blacklivesmatter #demonstratie #nos

snippet.title: We Cannot Remain Silent. Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
Dear Black America,
Your life matters. Black lives matter. We hear you, see you and mourn with you. Please know YOU ARE NOT ALONE.

Having received 60+ videos from dancers nationwide, this is a short version of a video we created; part 2 will release tomorrow. The end of the video contains suggestions of what you can do to support #blacklivesmatter. Thank you to all who took the time to send us a video, and a special thank you to @mulattaballerina for sharing such powerful words.

snippet.title: Change Is Gonna Come - Jai' Eagle | #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
It's a strange world that we all live in. As a black population, we have been fighting for respect, equal opportunity, and the god-given right to be alive since the beginning of our time. As tired as we are, we won't stop fighting.

I pray for justice for George, Breonna, and Ahmaud. I pray for the safety of every single person that is taking a stand against the injustice in this country. I pray for every single family that has felt the wrath of the disgusting realities that we face each day and that healing, comfort, and will to continue to live embraces them everyday. I pray for our children , and their children, and their children...that they may hopefully only learn of these times in their history books. 

The time for this to end was yesterday. 

I do not own the rights to this music. Originally performed by the legendary Sam Cooke.

Watch Rabbi Reuven Wolf Live @ Maayon Yisroel!
—
Thank you for watching this video. I hope that you keep up with the daily videos I post on the channel, subscribe, and share your learnings with those that need to hear it. Your comments are always welcome, so please take a second and say ‘Hi’  ;)

—

http://maayonyisroel.com/

—
#RabbiReuvenWolf
Rabbi Reuven Wolf is a world renowned educator and lecturer who has devoted his life to reaching out and rekindling the spirit of Judaism in his fellow Jews. Recognized as an inspiring and thought provoking lecturer, he has cultivated a unique talent to communicate deep and complex mystical ideas in a manner that is both compelling and applicable to the greater public, and his lessons are charged with an enthusiasm and vigor that impacts listeners both intellectually and emotionally. Rabbi Wolf was raised in the Ropshetz Chassidic dynasty, educated in the Belz and Bluzhev Yeshivos, and later, in the famous Lithuanian schools of Slabodkea and Mir. He is profoundly influenced by Jewish Mysticism and Kabbalah, and particularly Chabad Chassidic philosophy.

Since 1995, Rabbi Wolf has been teaching students of all ages, from elementary school children to adults, and has lectured across North America. #MaayonYisroel was founded in 2006 by Rabbi Wolf and Haki Abhesera, as a center to fulfill the vision of spreading the profound mystical teachings of #Chassidus

The name "Maayon Yisroel," which means "wellsprings of Israel," is indicative of our mission to enrich and inspire the Jewish people with the deep, mystical teachings of the Baal Shem Tov and other Chassidic masters.

Rabbi Yisroel Baal Shem Tov, a 16th century Jewish mystic, was renowned for his unconditional love for the Jewish People, who worked to bring together Jews of all types to be inspired and nurtured in their appreciation of and relationship with G-d.

Through principles derived from his teachings, we aim to follow in the noble tradition of rejuvenating Yiddishkeit by showing how mystical ideas can be applied to modern life. These concepts which until now, have been largely inaccessible to the English-speaking public, have the power to provide the spirituality that Jews today complain is so often lacking in their experience of Judaism, as a mechanical and technical series of laws.

Check out my Spotify Podcast:
http://www.maayon.com/spotify

snippet.title: Hadestown Chant with Black Lives Matter Protests
snippet.description:
**I do not own the pictures or sound, which belongs to the soundtrack from the musical Hadestown**

Considering the horrific events that took place when George Floyd was killed by a Minneapolis police officer and the subsequent protests in the Twin Cities and then the country, I made this video to compare these protests/riots to those that took place last month in Michigan.  Please pray that the protesters around the nation will be able to mourn and respect Mr. Floyd's life peacefully without further police disturbances.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Hello,
I am really sad about what is happening in the world right now, what happened to George Floyd is truly disgusting and it wasn't the first time, things like this shouldn't been happening.
I wanted to make this video to raise awareness about the situation, things really need to change, we are all humans and we all need to be treated equally and with respect. 
I also thought it was important to include the scene where the police officer joins the protestants because I have seen many hate against police officers and a lot of unnecessary violence, please don't get confused on who the enemy is, don't hurt innocent people's properties and remember an eye for an eye makes the whole world blind.
If you want to help please do it fairly.
Thank you for watching and remember to be kind to others.

Jureth x


WAYS TO HELP : https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/

#blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Justice for George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Arbery, Toni McDade, and all black people affected by police violence, profiling, and the carceral state in general. Use this momentum, demand change, do your own work, find your lane, and work harder and better right now. 
This moment is for focusing on Black Lives Matter, but that's a low (but horrifyingly necessary) bar. Everyone should have justice and be able to thrive- that can't happen until Black and Indigenous and LGBTQ+ and disabled people all truly matter and the system acknowledges and supports that- the system needs to change. 
Healthcare inequities and environmental degradation are intersecting problems that include racism and bigotry as well, and need to be worked on simultaneously- walk and chew gum everyone, and don't let up. It's long past time.

snippet.title: Why Black Lives Matter is important - part 1 (with Oh Hey It's Double A) - Pizza Time Episode 13
snippet.description:
On this episode of Pizza Time myself and Oh Hey It's Double A (a.k.a Aaron) host a 2 part Podcast series. In this 2 part series, myself and Aaron host an all-black panel to talk about George Floyd’s Death, Black Lives Matter, racism in today’s society and a lot more
This is part 1 of the podcast but part 2 is now available on Oh Hey It's Double A's podcast called Round Table. Here are the links to his show and his youtube channel (part 2 will not be on YouTube channel but he has lots of great content coming soon)
Spotify: https://open.spotify.com/show/3FT7Ct5BboPnM2SPtPyQ9g?si=5ApHT-EURMOs_a18ubC81A
Apple Podcast: https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/round-table/id1498986859
Spotify: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC87TnS6XKq2BXIDZPgd9o2Q

Thank you to our all black panel for coming on and sharing your thoughts and experiences

To support the movement use this link for Petitions, places to donate, other useful resources: https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/

To buy a Black Lives Matter t-shirt with all profits going to Black Lives Matter movement use this link: https://teespring.com/black-lives-mater-ws?tsmac=store&tsmic=wildeshop&pid=389&cid=100029
or to donate directly to them use this one: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/ms_blm_homepage_2019

snippet.title: Which South Africa Trending | Black Lives Matter | Twitter |Whats Trending SA with Neo Poho episode2
snippet.description:
Demonstrators filled the streets across the US on Sunday to once again protest police brutality and the death of George Floyd, an unarmed black man who died at the hands of a police officer in Minneapolis.

Crowds wearing masks to ward off coronavirus clogged streets and stopped traffic. What started as peaceful protests sometimes turned violent. Stores were looted and burned and police pelted with rocks and bottles. Hundreds of people have been arrested.
Cities extended curfews into Sunday night and beyond in an attempt to tamp down the violence and vandalism.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter 2020 Vs Sarafina 1992 Police Brutalities
snippet.description: This describes today society whats happening in the world. The Good Die Young, yeah right! People Disappear....how long will they let the good people speak? Sarafina is a young black south African struggles for freedom during the apartheid. While she has remained relatively silent in her opposition of the racist government in her country. The teacher played by Whoop Goldberg to dream of a better tomorrow. The teacher makes statements in her classroom that sound like common sense to us but like communism to the south African authorities who arrest her and take her away. Same quote like Donald Trump: When the looting starts, the shooting starts! This is war! It was first used by Miami Police chief Walter Headley in the 1960's when he sent officers with shotguns and dogs to patrol black neighborhoods. I don't give a shit how young you are. You throw a bomb at me, I'm going to kill you. You try to burn down my house, I'm going to kill you. You make war on my country, I'm going to kill you. You think you've got the whole of black Africa just waiting to roll on over us, eh? You try it. Just try it. We're ready for you.

localized.description: This describes today society whats happening in the world. The Good Die Young, yeah right! People Disappear....how long will they let the good people speak? Sarafina is a young black south African struggles for freedom during the apartheid. While she has remained relatively silent in her opposition of the racist government in her country. The teacher played by Whoop Goldberg to dream of a better tomorrow. The teacher makes statements in her classroom that sound like common sense to us but like communism to the south African authorities who arrest her and take her away. Same quote like Donald Trump: When the looting starts, the shooting starts! This is war! It was first used by Miami Police chief Walter Headley in the 1960's when he sent officers with shotguns and dogs to patrol black neighborhoods. I don't give a shit how young you are. You throw a bomb at me, I'm going to kill you. You try to burn down my house, I'm going to kill you. You make war on my country, I'm going to kill you. You think you've got the whole of black Africa just waiting to roll on over us, eh? You try it. Just try it. We're ready for you.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! #JusticeForGeorgeFloyd #JusticeForTina #JusticeForUwa | Coffee Table Gist
snippet.description:
Wake Up Nigeria, June 1, 2020

On the coffee Table gist, Yomi Owope and Tope Olowoniyan spoke about the outrage going on in the world. The recent killing of a black man, #GeorgeFlyod in Minneapolis, US has led to mass protest across the country. Now, the killing of young girls in Nigeria? What's actually going on? 💔

Uwaila Omozuwa was just 22-years-old and a first year student of University Of Benin.What did she or her parents do wrong?
Tina was just 16-years-old and was innocent, but was hit by a bullet on Tuesday 26th May, when a police officer shot to disperse a crowd that had gathered after he opened fire on a bus driver who broke curfew rules.
Jennifer was another 12-year-old raped by 11 men.

snippet.description:

Following the recent killing of George Floyd, many persons have been protesting across different state in the United States...video footage clearly shows Floyd being cuffed faced down and was kneeled on by 3 police officers one of whom was seeing kneeling in his neck... Floyd could be heard crying out “I can’t breathe” to which the officers showed no remorse...we stand with our black brothers and sister in this march for justice for Floyd and all the other black lives that was brutally taken away... “I can’t breathe”....black lives matter!!!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Justice For Floyd | I condemn this act of barbarism | Augustina Ekwunife
snippet.description:
#Black_lives_matter #Justice_for_floyd #augustina_ekwunife

I couldn't watch the video ... It was so disturbing. Such act of barbarism.  Why such brutality and evil? Why so inhuman?
#GeorgeFloyd was handcuffed and lying on the ground.  3 men against him. So why the violence???
These are questions I keep ASKING myself over and over. 

I condemn such act. Not talk of the fact that he was an officer. He was supposed to PROTECT that man's life. I am speechless and saddened.  It's horrible!

I pray this never repeat AGAIN.  That cop is a disgrace to the force.  A disgrace to the nation of America.  A disgrace to manhood.  A disgrace to the his family. 

And all those colleagues of his that was watching WITHOUT doing anything to stop him. They did nothing to prevent George Floyd's death. All if them are complice and should be arrested as well. JUSTICE must prevail. 

If we must create a world for our children in the future where It is possible to LIVE and not be afraid of being killed like a rat... Then we have to STAND up and say ENOUGH! And the time to do that is NOW, not tomorrow. 

We don't have to keep silent.  We all speak up. We must be Floyds VOICE now...
May his soul rest in peace. Amen!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | No to racial discrimination | USA | 2020 | Religions Revealed against Racism
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international human rights movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

In 2013, the movement began with the use of the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the acquittal of George Zimmerman in the shooting death of African-American teen Trayvon Martin in February 2012. The movement became nationally recognized for street demonstrations following the 2014 deaths of two African Americans: Michael Brown—resulting in protests and unrest in Ferguson, a city near St. Louis—and Eric Garner in New York City.[2][3] Since the Ferguson protests, participants in the movement have demonstrated against the deaths of numerous other African Americans by police actions or while in police custody. In the summer of 2015, Black Lives Matter activists became involved in the 2016 United States presidential election. The originators of the hashtag and call to action, Alicia Garza, Patrisse Cullors, and Opal Tometi, expanded their project into a national network of over 30 local chapters between 2014 and 2016. The overall Black Lives Matter movement, however, is a decentralized network and has no formal hierarchy.

There have been many reactions to the Black Lives Matter movement. The U.S. population's perception of Black Lives Matter varies considerably by race. The phrase "All Lives Matter" sprang up as a response to the Black Lives Matter movement, but has been criticized for dismissing or misunderstanding the message of "Black Lives Matter". Following the shooting of two police officers in Ferguson, the hashtag Blue Lives Matter was created by supporters of the police. Some civil rights leaders have disagreed with tactics used by Black Lives Matter activists.] By the summer of 2017, the movement was receiving less media attention, which some people attributed to Donald Trump's presidency dominating national headlines.

The movement returned to national headlines during the George Floyd protests.

localized.title: Black Lives Matter | No to racial discrimination | USA | 2020 | Religions Revealed against Racism
localized.description:
Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international human rights movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

In 2013, the movement began with the use of the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the acquittal of George Zimmerman in the shooting death of African-American teen Trayvon Martin in February 2012. The movement became nationally recognized for street demonstrations following the 2014 deaths of two African Americans: Michael Brown—resulting in protests and unrest in Ferguson, a city near St. Louis—and Eric Garner in New York City.[2][3] Since the Ferguson protests, participants in the movement have demonstrated against the deaths of numerous other African Americans by police actions or while in police custody. In the summer of 2015, Black Lives Matter activists became involved in the 2016 United States presidential election. The originators of the hashtag and call to action, Alicia Garza, Patrisse Cullors, and Opal Tometi, expanded their project into a national network of over 30 local chapters between 2014 and 2016. The overall Black Lives Matter movement, however, is a decentralized network and has no formal hierarchy.

There have been many reactions to the Black Lives Matter movement. The U.S. population's perception of Black Lives Matter varies considerably by race. The phrase "All Lives Matter" sprang up as a response to the Black Lives Matter movement, but has been criticized for dismissing or misunderstanding the message of "Black Lives Matter". Following the shooting of two police officers in Ferguson, the hashtag Blue Lives Matter was created by supporters of the police. Some civil rights leaders have disagreed with tactics used by Black Lives Matter activists.] By the summer of 2017, the movement was receiving less media attention, which some people attributed to Donald Trump's presidency dominating national headlines.

The movement returned to national headlines during the George Floyd protests.

#blacklivesmatter #notoracism #bethechange #religions #revealed #unity #usa #BlackLivesMatter #peace #africanamerican

snippet.title: BREATHLESS - Original song - BLACK LIVES MATTER
snippet.description:
‘Breathless’ is an original song against police brutality and racism.

VIOLENCE is not the solution.
SILENCE is an easy solution but it not help at all. So I decided to raise my voice my way.

DISCLAIMER : 
I'm not a native English-speaker. If there's any mistake about the English, I apologize for that. Please, no hate !!! 

I am aware that I will never know how does it feel to be oppressed because of my skin color. However I've got eyes to see all this pain and this disgusting brutality against black people in the world. I want to help, I want to stand by them.

BLACK LIVES MATTER
RACISM MUST STOP 
POLICE BRUTALITY MUST STOP

#blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: Police Officer takes a knee outside Downing Street at Black Lives Matter march in London
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A police officer outside Downing Street was filmed taking the knee alongside protesters marching in solidarity with Black Lives Matter.

Thousands gathered in Hyde Park on Wednesday before marching on Parliament Square in response to the killing of George Floyd in the US.

Traffic was blocked in certain areas as some climbed on phone boxes and sculptures with megaphones to whip up loud chants of "silence is violence" and "say his name, George Floyd".​

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-police-office-take-knee-downing-street-a4459081.html

snippet.title: Speak Up- Black Lives Matter! ✊🏾 | With Love Jenae'
snippet.description:
✊🏾 Black. Lives. Matter. ✊🏾
Our country is once again in an uproar over the senseless killing of black people. We are living in some crazy times and more and more we are seeing that people don't really value black lives. Black lives STILL matter. 

My opinions may be unpopular. But to premier my Youtube page without addressing the obvious would be irresponsible. This was an impromptu video but I said what I felt needed to be said about what is going on. 

My beautiful black kings and queens, keep fighting. Keep speaking up. Be wise and be safe in these crazy times. Educate yourselves on what you can do to help be part of the solution and not the problem. That goes for EVERYONE. And more than anything- PRAY, PRAY, PRAY!!! Despite the chaos, God is able. And I'm holding on to that. You should too.

I've tagged some petitions at the bottom of this description. PLEASE if you can sign them and donate if you have the means to! Every little bit helps.


✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾BLACK LIVES MATTER. TODAY. EVERYDAY. AND ALWAYS.✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾

Thank you so much for checking out my video! Be sure to like, comment, subscribe, and turn on those alerts because I'm coming back with bangers! 💥💥💥💥💥

snippet.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
snippet.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

localized.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
localized.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.

snippet.title: Que es Black Lives Matter?
snippet.description:
Hola! Gracias por venir a mi canal y por ver este video. Se que no se trata de ser mama ni de maquillaje, pero ahorita es importante de dialogar sobre este tema para todos los Hispanos/Latinos que no entienden o no saben lo qué pasa. Ojalá este video les ayude a entender; por favor compártanlo con sus amigos y familiares para que ellos puedan entender también. Muchas gracias.

snippet.title: Sydney Police pepper spray Black Lives Matter protesters
snippet.description:
Sydney's Black Lives Matters protests have taken a dark turn after a police officer was captured pepper spraying a group of protesters at Central Station. 

Footage posted to social media showed at least one officer spraying into the crowd as demonstrators and police clashed.

At least half a dozen people were treated following the incident.

Another man was dragged away by police and later handcuffed, however it's understood he was not charged.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter सोशल मीडिया पर क्यों कर रहा ट्रेंड?
snippet.description:
2008 में बराक ओबामा जब राष्ट्रपति बने तो लगा कि अमेरिका में नस्लीय हिंसा की बहस अब खत्म हो जाएगी लेकिन 2020 में राष्ट्रपति डॉनल्ड ट्रंप के कार्यकाल खत्म होते-होते अमेरिका इसी बहस पर जल रहा है. ट्रम्प प्रदर्शकारियों को रोकने के लिए सेना को धमकी तो दे रहे हैं लेकिन अश्वेतो के खिलाफ हिंसा को रोकने पर वो चुप्पी साधे बैठे हैं. तमाम दुनिया में सोशल मीडिया प्लेटफॉर्म पर ट्रेंड कर रहा है #blacklivesmatter जिसका मतलब हुआ अश्वेतों की जान भी मायने रखती है..

localized.description:
2008 में बराक ओबामा जब राष्ट्रपति बने तो लगा कि अमेरिका में नस्लीय हिंसा की बहस अब खत्म हो जाएगी लेकिन 2020 में राष्ट्रपति डॉनल्ड ट्रंप के कार्यकाल खत्म होते-होते अमेरिका इसी बहस पर जल रहा है. ट्रम्प प्रदर्शकारियों को रोकने के लिए सेना को धमकी तो दे रहे हैं लेकिन अश्वेतो के खिलाफ हिंसा को रोकने पर वो चुप्पी साधे बैठे हैं. तमाम दुनिया में सोशल मीडिया प्लेटफॉर्म पर ट्रेंड कर रहा है #blacklivesmatter जिसका मतलब हुआ अश्वेतों की जान भी मायने रखती है..

snippet.title: 2020 Peaceful Protest - Black Lives Matter  - Jackson, Michigan
snippet.description:
June 1, 2020 Passionate, Peaceful Protest in Jackson, Michigan organized by Akearah Anderson.

Join the Jackson community at Lily Missionary Baptist Church in Jackson, Michigan Saturday June 6, 2020 to Honor the Lives Lost to Racial Injustices.

TEXT -
FLOYD to 55156 to demand that the officers who murdered George Floyd are charged with murder.
ENOUGH to 55156 to demand justice for Breonna Taylor. The officers who murdered her still have their jobs.
JUSTICE to 55156 to demand that the District Attorneys involved in Ahmaud Arbery's case are removed from office.

Read about HR-40 
https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/40

RESEARCH HR -40 / WRITE REPRESENTATIVES / REGISTER TO VOTE 

Learn about leaders and speakers, reach out to them if needed to talk about your difficulties, experiences or help with voting. 

Daniel Mahoney - District 7 Commissioner, Jackson, MI
https://www.co.jackson.mi.us/1196/District-7---Daniel-J-Mahoney

Learn about Hakim Nathaniel Crampton, Motivational Speaker and Commissioner at Michigan Indigent Defense Commission. 
https://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/2014/02/spoken-word_poet_hakim_crampto.htmlhttps://michiganidc.gov/michigan-indigent-defense-commission/#toggle-id-14

https://jlusa.org/leader/hakim-nathaniel-crampton/
http://amen4youth.yolasite.com

Read Survivor Joseph Hines Story
https://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/2017/02/pastors_son_loses_appeal_in_po.htmlhttps://

Listen more to Pastor Hines at the event
https://youtu.be/s5j9aGnYmPk and at church home www.lilybaptist.com/ 

Derek Dobies, Mayor
https://www.facebook.com/derekdobies

Donate to Mama Tu-Tu, 517-787-8408 or 517-414-0932.122 W. Biddle, Jackson, MI 49203

Thank You to all the passionate speakers and people involved with this event and in our community of Jackson to keep it peaceful.

If you spoke in this video and I haven't mentioned your name please email us at dreamrealphotovideo@gmail.com

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
Websites for Action:
**Ant-racism resources for white people---- https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BRlF2_zhNe86SGgHa6-VlBO-QgirITwCTugSfKie5Fs/preview?pru=AAABcn--0n0*U3bBsVcR7D8Nxl1mlCzWjQ
**Anti-racism resources----  https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BRlF2_zhNe86SGgHa6-VlBO-QgirITwCTugSfKie5Fs/preview?pru=AAABcnX07hc*Pm8gUUGqTq4TxCwAWKNadg&fbclid=IwAR3-dwYsW4TPvHirXIz6W7CVJao68mYONY3xOxA4lBt7MATY5saVwFvU-fg
**How to safely and ethically film police misconduct----  https://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-to-film-police-safely

TEXT for Change:
**FLOYD to 55156 to demand that the officers who murdered George Floyd are charged with murder.
**ENOUGH to 55156 to demand justice for Breonna Taylor. The officers who murdered her still have their jobs.
**JUSTICE to 55156 to demand that the District Attorneys involved in Ahmaud Arbery's case are removed from office.

DONATE for Change:
**local bail fund. Protesters are being arrested and needing to be bailed out.
**Minnesota ACLU
**George Floyd’s family gofundme
**Justice 4 Jamar: a grassroots organization that helped organize the, protest yesterday and regularly organizes protests and support for individuals and their families impacted by police violence in Minneapolis.  
**Black Vision Collective, Minneapolis-based Black Lives Matter group 
**Black Lives Matter, National Black Lives Matter

CALL for Justice:
**Minneapolis Mayor Jacob Frey (612) 673-2100
**Minnesota Governor Tim Walz: (651) 201-3400
**District Attorney Mike Freeman (612) 348-5550  **request he pass the case on to Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison in addition to reading the suggested script below: 
"My name is (FULL NAME). I am calling to demand that murder charges be filed against Derek Chauvin #1087 and Tou Thao #7162 as well as any additional officers at the scene for the murder of George Floyd. I am also demanding that there be no grand jury barrier before charges are filed. And that loud support and action should be behind legislation to abolish paid leave for violence committed against citizens as well as barriers for hiring/firing offenses be put in place for officers with a history of violence against citizens as evidence of likely escalation of violence. These murders have a chilling effect on the entire population. I and many others do not feel safe calling the police for fear of the violence they will commit. I refuse to be a catalyst of someone's murder."

SEND A LETTER:
**The Estate of George Floyd, c/o Ben Crump Law, PLLC, 122 S. Calhoun St., Tallahassee, FL 32301, Attn: Adner Marcelin

INFORMATION and Resources for Caring for Ourselves and Others
Meditation Exercises:
**Black Lives Matters Meditation for Healing Racial Trauma by Dr. Candice Nicole
**Soulfulness 4 Life

APPS:
**Liberate app: Liberate is the #1 meditation app for the Black, Indigenous and People of Color community. Listen to dozens of guided meditations to ease anxiety, find gratitude, heal internalized racism and microaggressions, and celebrate Blackness. 
**The Safe Place: a Minority Mental Health App geared towards the Black Community to bring awareness, education and hope. 

PODCASTS:
**The Breakdown with Dr. Earl: A Mental Health Podcast
**The Homecoming Podcast with Dr. Thema﻿

Info on mail in Ballet Info---  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l-nEHkgm_Gk

snippet.title: LL Cool J and Kalparkr - Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd (Official Demo Audio)
snippet.description:
We believe that black lives matter! This is LL Cool J's and Kalparkr's Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd as well as every black person that has been killed, racially profiled or harassed! LL Cool J gave a powerful speech that completely embodies the hurt blacks are still going through all over the world. 

Below is  the summary of the George Floyd incident that lead to his death. 
 On May 25, 2020, George Floyd, an African-American man, died in the Powderhorn community of Minneapolis, Minnesota. 

While Floyd was handcuffed and lying face down on a city street during an arrest, Derek Chauvin, a white American Minneapolis police officer, kept his knee on the right side of Floyd's neck for 8 minutes and 46 seconds; according to the criminal complaint against Chauvin, 2 minutes and 53 seconds of that time occurred after Floyd became unresponsive. Officers Tou Thao, J. Alexander Kueng, and Thomas K. Lane participated in Floyd's arrest, with Kueng holding Floyd's back, Lane holding his legs, and Thao looking on and forcibly preventing intervention by onlookers as he stood nearby.

Sad😢 to see the harm that some police officers inflict based on suspicion. Let us all pray for them today that they'll be patient enough to resolve matters without first breaking wrists, body slamming, shooting or disgracing us. Let there be peace on earth! Don't be quiet!

George Floyd is not the only Black American male that has perished in such a hateful manner but the people are taking a stand against this injustice in 2020.

Lyrics for Chorus:

They want us to be , silent! But this time that's gonna be hard
We believe we got to build a defense where we can shelter from this war

We'll take this no longer, longer, longer, no!
Raise your fists say black lives matter
Together we are stronger, stronger, stronger, yeah!
Shout it again black lives matter!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protests spread to streets of Australia
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters have flouted social distancing restrictions by marching through the Sydney CBD in solidarity with demonstrators in the US over the death of George Floyd.

The 'Black Lives Matter' rally started in Hyde Park before making its way to State Parliament. 

Authorities said the protest remained entirely peaceful and no arrests were made. 

A second, larger rally is scheduled for the weekend.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Powerful Messages and Lessons Amid George Floyd Protests.
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER is currently fighting perceived systematic police racism in the US, following the deaths of black men being taken into custody or shot by officers. Here is a compilation of some of the most poignant quotes from activists and supporters.

Celebrities, public figures, politicians, and activists have all come out to bat for Black Lives Matter amidst social unrest in the US. These notable figures have released statements and appeared at rallies to back people behind the cause. Their words remain a vital sustaining influence, spreading the message to people who may not otherwise have taken action.

00:00 - 00:47, Black Lives matter quotes: Powerful messages and lessons amid George Floyd protests (Image: GETTY).

00:48 - 02:07, Black Lives matter quotes: BLM co-founder Patrisse Cullors said she wants black people to "feel and be free" (Image: GETTY).

02:08 - 03:11, Black Lives matter quotes: Alicia Garza called for deep systemic changes in the wake of the protests (Image: GETTY).

03:11 - 04:15, Black Lives matter quotes: Akilah Hughes has called on white people to "practice and get better" (Image: GETTY).

Thanks in advance for watching, liking, and leaving feedback. Hit the "Subscribe" button to join our community and be notified every time we post some emotional quotes. Your warm support will inspire the creation of more emotional quotes.

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter?" By Mr Coleman
snippet.description:
"Black Lives Matter?"
Mr Coleman


I ask myself does black lives matter/ When our hands up but blood still splatter/ Unlawful acts being displayed constant heart rates going flatter/Excuse my slang but the community is upset and is getting madder/ We ask for justice but all we receive is excuses/ Lower the value of our people trying to make us feel useless/ What we see on tape is uniforms being ruthless/ Being spoon fed a bunch of articles and reports that's  truthless/ Yeah we fed up! enough is enough it's time to stand up and make a change/(Hmmm) Just looking back a couple months ago makes wonder how a strong voice like that still have the hood looking the same/ Does black lives matter Because my observation of the situation/ See a big double standard that conflicts our argument that we are making/ When it's the other kind we are righteous but when it's our own kind there's not one statement/ Families on their knees crying while slang bodies laying on the pavement/ Our own communities are no longer safe havens/ Playing the roles of God with the lives that we are taking/ It's simple and plain/ they see us as untamed/ Black folks who are wild and insane/ We can't make folks respect us if we can't do the same/ We participating in our own genocide/ With self inflicting homicides/ Prayers as we look up to the sky/ While asking the lord why/ Why my baby had to take that hearse ride/ Why my Cousin had to be there when them unregistered bullets had to fly/ Why is my mom tears watering plants because my brother had to die/ I have came to the conclusion that Only a sense of pride will make things matter/ Until we reach that point we will be nothing but a punchline received nothing but laughter/ Black Lives Matter


☆Don't forget to Subscribe, Like and Comment☆

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER JUSTICE NO MATTER
snippet.description:
I wrote this poem the other day based on one of my favourite quotes. 
The system wasn’t made to serve everyone. The system fails a lot of people. I see that. I want to fight that. I want to change that. 
I have my words. I have my privilege. I urge everyone to use their white privilege for the better. To not loose momentum long after the Instagram stories stop. After the donations dwindle. I urge you to carry on the fight. To remember these feelings. To remember these cries. 
I urge you to never forget. 
There’s a protest here in Manchester on Saturday at 1pm. I’ll post on my stories about it. 
Let’s use our voices until we see the change we really need. 
The change our brothers and sisters need !!!! This is our problem too ! 
#blacklivesmatter 
@donte.colley @florencegiven @troubletongues

snippet.title: VLOG: Black Lives Matter & Waking up the collective consciousness
snippet.description:
This is the 2nd video 
As people started to speak up in outrage
Looking at my Timeline I felt like I was yelling at a wall
Whilst not wanting to go for people or make divisive statements
It was clear that we were all witnessing systemic injustice and oppression and some people chose to remain silent, or sent teary eyes but were not investing themselves in the situation or asking the important questions like

HOW DID THIS HAPPEN?

WHAT CAN I DO?

Well meaning smileys and crying faces just like you would to a cat video is not the appropriate reaction to a planned out murder and the type of police brutality you see in this video.

This video is also honouring the legacy of people of all races, who have not been offended by the blanket statement of "white priviledge" or the visceral words thrust at them by some hurt members of my community but have stood by us and are standing by us in this moment when we need the most.
Women like Juliette Hampton Morgan and Virginia Foster Durr & men like James Reeb and many more who must and will be recognised sacrificed a lot to stand with us - this is their duty as human beings and prisoners of conscience. But in this day and age many people will not even sacrifice one swift movement of their thumb to like or share or sign a petition which is the least one can do.

As a man I cant help but wish I could have 1 or 2 hours alone with the policeman who was punching that woman, watching these videos and immersing myself in their pain was very distressing, so im grateful to all who chose not to look away

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Tribute | A Video Tribute for George Floyd
snippet.description:
Last May 25, 2020, Minneapolis police officers arrested George Floyd, a 46-year-old black man, accusing him of buying cigarettes with a counterfeit bill. 

Security footage and bystanders videos show how a series of actions by officers turned fatal. After 8 minutes and 46 seconds, George Floyd was unconscious and pinned beneath three police officers, showing no signs of life.

Protests continue across the United States, even worldwide, more than a week after the death of George Floyd.

Let us all stand against police brutality and racial discrimination. 

Black Lives Matter

snippet.title: Thousands in London protest to say 'Black Lives Matter'
snippet.description:

The crowds chanted "I can't breathe" -- a reference to the death of George Floyd, in Minneapolis, who was killed when a policeman knelt on his neck.

Sky's Home Affairs editor Jason Farrell reports from London.

snippet.title: Glasgow says Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The murder of George Floyd has brought worldwide attention to the systemic, anti-black racism that continues to exist in America and beyond. This includes in our own city, Glasgow, which has not yet confronted the legacy of its slave trading past.

In the 1700s Glasgow grew rapidly, becoming the ‘second city of Empire’, thanks largely to its role in the cotton, sugar and tobacco trades. The city’s merchants controlled much of the global trade in these commodities, owning plantations in America and the West Indies where tens of thousands of slaves toiled for their Glaswegian masters.

Many of Glasgow’s most famous streets were built off the back of slave labour, and named after the city’s celebrated ‘tobacco lords’.

We have now added alternative names to some of these streets to mark the legacy of slavery – celebrating those who rebelled against it and who fought for its abolition, and for civil rights and liberation. We also remember those who continue to bear the brunt of bias and police brutality, three centuries on.

Joseph Knight was taken from Africa to a sugar plantation in Jamaica owned by a wealthy Scottish landowner who later brought him back to Scotland. Knight escaped and fought against his former master in court, ensuring that slavery was illegal in Scotland.

Harriet Tubman was born into slavery in the American state of Maryland before escaping at the age of 27. She helped set hundreds more free, including when leading a daring raid on a plantation fighting for the anti-slavery side in the American Civil War.

Rosa Parks was another brilliant woman who struck one of the first blows for equal rights in America. From Montgomery, Alabama, Parks by law had to sit at the back of public buses and give up her seat to any white passengers who needed one. On the first day of December, 1955 she refused to do so, sparking the eventually successful campaign for civil rights in America.

Fred Hampton was born in Chicago in 1948. In his short life, he united the street gangs of Chicago against their common enemy – the racist state – and his leadership skills saw him rise through the ranks of the Black Panthers, a revolutionary organisation which fed the poor and challenged police brutality in black communities. Aged just 21, he was assassinated by the FBI.

Despite the advances won by Joseph Knight, Harriet Tubman, Rosa Parks, Fred Hampton and many others, black people continue to suffer from discrimination and to die at the hands of the state, here in Scotland, in America and elsewhere. 

In 2015, Sheku Bayoh, a 32 year old father from Kircaldy in Fife, was murdered by nine officers from Police Scotland, who used batons, CS gas and leg restraints on him. Sheku suffered 23 separate injuries and died from suffocation as police officers kneeled and lay on him for several minutes. He couldn’t breathe. The cops refused to talk for more than a month until they’d got their stories straight. No-one has ever faced justice for Sheku’s death, and his killers continue to walk the streets of Scotland.

Five years later, George Floyd died in very similar circumstances in Minnesota. Unlike the case of Sheku Bayoh, the cops involved now face the full weight of the law, which they had themselves applied on the neck of their helpless victim. 

George Floyd’s death provoked public outrage and has prompted many of us to examine our consciences, and our consciousness. We must now ask whether Glasgow should continue to celebrate the names of the city’s slave masters instead of icons of the fight against slavery and for equal rights, and why we are not demanding justice for Sheku Bayoh and George Floyd and an end to bias and police brutality. Where Glasgow once led the world’s slave-reliant industries, it must now lead in tackling racism.

snippet.title: Peaceful Black Lives Matter Protesters Get Creative | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 

From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" by Fanta Ballo
snippet.description:
BLACKLIVESMATTER, We will not be silenced. Spoken Word Poetry 

“Say Our Names, Remember Our Faces” , I have been sitting on this poem for a while because every time I read it I get angry and feel like I cant give the poem justice. The truth is our black bodies have been dying at the hands of corrupt police officers. We don't even know the names of some of these people because their stories don't make it mainstream. As I was making this video I see that there are way more people who die at the hands of police than we even know. After the heinous killing of Ahmaud Aubrey, I feel like this had to be posted. Sadly Ahmaud Aubrey won't be the last Black person killed at the hands of White Supremacy, there needs to be change but let's not ever forget our fallen soldiers.

Welcome to my channel !! Here I will post my original poetry videos. Please give it a listen and let me know what you think. 

Let me know your favorite line ! Open to all feedback. 

Road to 1k. 

#BLM #Blacklivematter #StopKillingUs

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! By YmX
snippet.description:
Recent events have taken a toll on me and I'd normally keep quiet for the fear of being misunderstood or not saying the right words but I'm learning that I have a responsibility to use my voice in the face of injustice and nothing will be achieved through silence! 

So here I am, using my 'voice' and this is only the beginning...

We are in this together and we need to support each other and continue to use our voices or anything we have, and one day, when the glory comes...It will be ours!

Over the past few days, the LowKeys have participated in and officially sponsored the “Freedom Fundraiser,” show, a benefit concert organized by the Harvard arts community, to raise money for organizations and communities affected by police violence. This video is our attempt to use our voices as a community-- including alumni-- to raise money to combat police brutality, support bail relief and public health efforts, and firmly state our commitment to the Black Lives Matter movement. All the organizations listed are collectives aimed at supporting black protestors, activists and organizers. With love and in solidarity. 

The Harvard LowKeys perform "Amazing Grace." 

Soloist: Samyra Miller '21
Introduction: Uzo Ngwu '23
Video Production: Jake Schwencke '21
Arrangers: Sam Murdock '23, Samyra Miller '21, Mikaël Scaramucci '21

snippet.title: LA PLUMA DE VICTOR #44.- BLACK LIVES MATTER (LIBROS SOBRE LA NEGRITUD)
snippet.description:
Hoy, con motivo de las protestas raciales en Estados Unidos, hablamos de novelas que nos permitan conocer un poco más de lo que hay en juego allí. La literatura a veces da el marco de pensamiento, comparte la experiencia, y transmite la angustia de ser negro (afroamericano, o de cualquier otra latitud) y el racismo en algunos países.

Está estructurado en 3 partes.

CRECER EN EEUU.- Hablamos en esta parte de la obra capital de Maya Angelou "yo sé porque canta el pájaro enjaulado", en la que narra su dura infancia y la combativa adolescencia llena de obstáculos y limitaciones para una mujer negra de su época. Un testimonio demoledor.

LA SOMBRA DE LA ESCLAVITUD.- Analizamos la huella de la esclavitud en dos claves, la fantasizacion del dolor para poder explicar algo tan crudo, como en EL FERROCARRIL SUBTERRANEO de Colson Whitehead o desde la crónica realista de una experiencia personal en "12 AÑOS DE ESCLAVITUD" de Solomon Northup.

SER NEGRA HOY EN DIA.- En la que damos cuenta de nuevas voces femeninas, que han logrado con libros testimoniales hacernos ver qué es y que se juega en el mundo una mujer negra hoy en día. Ya sea española de origen guineano como SER NEGRA EN ESPAÑA de Desiree Bela Lobedde, NIÑA, MUJER, OTRAS de Bernardine Evaristo (premio booker de este año) y la famosa AMERICANAH  de la nigeriana Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie.

OTRAS RECOMENDACIONES.- Como PROHIBIDO NACER de Trevor Noah, Notes on a Native son, de James Baldwyn o MATAR A UN RUISEÑOR, de Harper Lee...

snippet.title: Black lives matter song; Will I Be Okay : Suburban pain
snippet.description: Black lives matter I am tired of living in a world where my very existence feels like a threat. Black lives matter and I’ll say it once and I’ll say it again and I’ll scream it from the top of my lungs until the world understands that black lives matter. This has nothing to do with black or white and everything to do with human rights. I fight for a better life because I want my children to grow up in a world where people don’t see their blackness as a threat. And the only way I can make sure 100 percent that they don’t have to feel the same pain I did growing up is by using my voice and fighting and I urge you to do the same. Whether your black white Mexican Asian middle eastern etc please stand with us please stand for human rights please let our children grow up in a world where they don’t fear getting gunned down in the street if you have compassion spread the word use your voice have those uncomfortable conversations do it for a better future where all men women and anyone else in between can live in harmony and feel safe god bless you all and please stay safe. ✊🏿✊🏼✊🏾✊🏽✊🏾

snippet.title: Do Black Lives Matter in Medicine?
snippet.description:
Board certified ObGyn discusses race, healthcare disparities, racism, and medicine. What are the social and societal constructs of race and institutional racism that affect health and access to healthcare in the United States?

RESOURCES:
- ACOG Committee Opinion: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx
- Health Coverage for POC: http://kff.org/disparities-policy/fact-sheet/health-coverage-for-the-black-population-today-and-under-the-affordable-care-act
- Sterilized in the name of public health: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx#O10-57-2
- Patient-physician social concordance, medical visit communication & perception: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx#O12-57-2
- Resource List for Everyone to Be Less Racist:

snippet.title: Dr. King’s Dream | Spoken Word Poetry | Black Lives Matter Poem | I Can't Breathe
snippet.description:
(To make sure the video is clear, change your settings to HD Quality)

I became a Spoken Word Artist in 2015 when I wrote Dr. King’s Dream. It was my first spoken word poem and my visceral reaction to the death of Sandra Bland. I saw myself in her and could only express my pain in spoken word. The world owes a debt to Dr. King’s Dream. Martin Luther King fought for civil rights and to abolish racism. Sadly, his iconic I Have a Dream speech is still a dream. Everyday Black people are being killed for living their normal lives. It’s 2020 and Ahmaud Arbery was murdered while running and Breonna Taylor was murdered while sleeping. When will it end? When will Black Lives Matter? Where can we be safe? 

I pray for a better tomorrow and to maintain faith that can move mountains. I’m thankful my friends who urged me to make a poetry video/film. And also encouraged me to create a YouTube channel to share my Spoken Word Poetry with the world. 

Please share this video on your social platforms  and comment below if any part my poem resonated. Thank you. 

All music by Epidemic Sound

Support on Patreon: Herisa Stanislaus
