snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" es un chiste, denuncia una mujer negra valiente
snippet.description:
"Los racistas son ustedes" ... sin palabras, tienen que ver este discurso de esta mujer valiente. Por más personas como ella en el mundo.

Nota sobre la oradora: Su nombre es Nestride Yumga. Ella nació y creció en Camerún. Más tarde se mudaría a los Estados Unidos para unirse a su familia. Ella se aplicó en la escuela y obtuvo una Maestría en Administración de Salud y también membresía en la Sociedad Nacional de Honor. Además, ha sido sido una activa modelo de fashion, trabajando para clientes como Covergirl, Macy’s, Kohl’s, Clinque y muchos más.

Ella vino como inmigrante de un país africano, y porque trabajó duro y no se victimizó, tuvo éxito. Mientras tanto, en todo Estados Unidos, muchos han nacido y han sido criados aquí, pero porque han sido alimentados con ideologías victimarias progresistas, al tener las mismas oportunidades desde el momento en que nacen, se convierten en matones, vagabundos, vándalos y completamente dependientes del gobierno.

No, no hay "problema racial" en Estados Unidos, lo que sí hay es un mensaje ideológico, impulsado por la izquierda política, que debilita las mentes, las morales y el espíritu de esta joven generación que se traga cualquier cuento para excusar su propia irresponsabilidad.

➡️➡️➡️ Para más vídeos, síganme en Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/ConservadorCristiano/

snippet.title: George Floyd Memorial Workout | Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Say his name.

George Floyd.

Today we're going to remember Floyd and bring awareness to the racism that persists in our government and police systems.

When this memorial workout starts to become difficult, know that it doesn't scratch the surface of suffering countless Black Americans face on a daily basis.

"George Floyd"
9 Min. AMRAP (as many reps as possible)
5 Bar Facing Burpees + 1 Clean and Jerk (155lbs/135lbs)
10 Bar Facing Burpees + 2 Clean and Jerk
15 Bar Facing Burpees + 3 Clean and Jerk
Etc.
Wear a 20lbs weight vest throughout.

Some reasoning behind the design of the workout: 9 minutes is the amount of time an officer weighing roughly 155lbs knelt on the back of his neck, over $20, until Floyd suffocated.

Over and over again he said "I can't breathe" just like Eric Garner did in 2014. 6 years later and nothings changed. At one point he was crying out for his mother while he died from a man kneeling on him with his hands cuffed from behind his back.

When are we going to learn? This is what I know so this is where I'm starting.

I hope you'll join me in this workout but further more, I hope you start with what you know.

Check those around you who perpetuate racism, donate to the NAACP, Color of Change, and other organizations for the Black Lives Matters movement, research your city's police code and find if they're mandated to wear body cam, etc. 

If you're wanting to help with the black lives matter movement, below is a link to donate to the NAACAP Legal Defense Fund.

https://org2.salsalabs.com/o/6857/p/salsa/donation/common/public/?donate_page_KEY=16304&track=DUXXX1G&utm_source=2020searchgoogle&utm_medium=search&utm_campaign=searchevergreen&gclid=Cj0KCQjw_ez2BRCyARIsAJfg-ksdh060dvMuJ9jZczErthwDavom6a7YUiwH8htd02nKI12-SvHUWooaAsjFEALw_wcB

This workout was originally made by my man Peter, owner of WakandaFit LLC. Follow him and his business on IG and YouTube.

Peter's IG: https://www.instagram.com/peterabundant/
WakandaFit's IG: https://www.instagram.com/wakandafitllc/
Peter's Youtube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCnU2J8G0ztgS7usPRs6EUgQ
WakandaFit's YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC4A7jepcE-pXFKxXL_48K_A

Over and over again he said "I can't breathe" just like Eric Garner did in 2014. 6 years later and nothings changed. At one point he was crying out for his mother while he died from a man kneeling on him with his hands cuffed from behind his back.

When are we going to learn? This is what I know so this is where I'm starting.

I hope you'll join me in this workout but further more, I hope you start with what you know.

Check those around you who perpetuate racism, donate to the NAACP, Color of Change, and other organizations for the Black Lives Matters movement, research your city's police code and find if they're mandated to wear body cam, etc. 

If you're wanting to help with the black lives matter movement, below is a link to donate to the NAACAP Legal Defense Fund.

https://org2.salsalabs.com/o/6857/p/salsa/donation/common/public/?donate_page_KEY=16304&track=DUXXX1G&utm_source=2020searchgoogle&utm_medium=search&utm_campaign=searchevergreen&gclid=Cj0KCQjw_ez2BRCyARIsAJfg-ksdh060dvMuJ9jZczErthwDavom6a7YUiwH8htd02nKI12-SvHUWooaAsjFEALw_wcB

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY
snippet.description:
A PRAYER FOR ALL OUR BROTHERS AND SISTERS IN THIS TIME. 

Almighty Father,

Violence, anger and hate are running the streets that you have created. Satan has stolen, killed and destroyed what you have made for us. There is no peace in the land. There is no justice amongst your people. The sinful crimes of the enemy have made the hearts of your children heavy. Hear our cries heavenly King, see our pain O Righteous One and feel our hurt. 

Scripture says that “The Lord is a shelter for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble. Those who know your name trust in you, for you, O Lord, do not abandon those who search for you”, (Psalms 9:9-10). Let your children be reminded that in this season of pain, we must search for your grace to fall upon your people, so that you may restore peace and justice in the land.

Matthew 5:44 “But I say, love your enemies! Pray for those who persecute you!”

Father, we pray for those who persecute us and hate us, we declare a veil of protection over us all in this season. We pray that we may find refuge and security in your scriptures. We pray for the families that have lost loved ones to the unjust. We pray for our spirits to be filled with faith and strength so that we are able to cast away all works of satan. 

May your will and you will alone be done over the land. May your blessings be on your people. 

Psalms 46:10 “Be still, and know that I am God”

AMEN.

#BLACKLIVESMATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY

snippet.title: We Need To Talk About Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
We originally made this video last week and posted it to Instagram (https://bit.ly/2XRRsiI). Given how this situation has only escalated since then, we felt it was important for this message to go out to our core audience here on YouTube.
 
For more information on how you can help the Black Lives Matter movement, please visit https://blacklivesmatter.com. Donations from this video will be given to the NAACP who are working to ensure the political, educational, social, and economic equality of the Black Community. snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter | They don't care about us.
snippet.description:
Hey guys, so I wanted to give a break on posting edits to say something really important. I think you all know about what's going on, and I really felt like I needed to do something to spread the message of the movement, so I did this video to show my support to #BlackLivesMatter, this video doesn't show half of the brutality that these people suffer every day but I really want to make you guys reflect about racism and everything wrong with out society. This song is very special too, and I put scenes of people I admire, like Viola Davis, movies/series that shows us that we need to fight for what is right, I really like the speech of Katniss on Mockingjay, the series "When They See us"is just incredible, and I love "The Hate U Give" too... I was not worried about HD scenes, or anything like that, I just knew I needed to do something to show my support! Hope you guys can use this video to reflect, share this with your friends and let's be on the right side :) 

Sincerely, Holy Wolf.

WAYS YOU CAN HELP! https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters fill London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more
Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

snippet.description:

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Ensayo sobre la Cuestión Racial en EE.UU.
snippet.description:
Una reflexión sobre las causas profundas e históricas del problema racial en Estados Unidos.

Bibliografía:
1) Beckert (2015) Empire of Cotton: A New History of Global Capitalism
2) Baptist (2016) The Half Has Never Been Told: Slavery and the Making of American Capitalism 
3) Netflix (2018) "Explianed: Racial Wealth Gap" (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mqrhn8khGLM)
4) Genovese (1989) The Political Economy of Slavery: Studies in the Economy and Society of the Slave South
5) Ocón y da Ponte (2016) Industria y Defensa: Economía Política, Pensamiento Estratégico y Autonomía Tecnológica.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter chanting on LaSalle bridge, Chicago - May 31st, 2020 - Justice for George Floyd
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter taking over LaSalle bridge over River North in downtown Chicago around 7:30 pm May 31st, 2020 - Chicago protests Saturday May 30th - Justice for George Floyd

I recorded this video while walking around downtown Chicago on Sunday, May 31st, 2020. 

This is shortly before the police presence on horses and cars; not soon after after the police presence crossed to the north side of the river, where there is now a major presence around Trump Tower and surroundings.

#chicagoprotests #georgefloyd #blacklivesmatter #chicagoriots #looting #protests

snippet.title: Super United for Black Lives Matter Chill Fun Time Live Stream
snippet.description:
Instead of sketches and songs we're going to be hearing some text messages and voice mails from complete strangers who were nice enough to share their feelings at this wild and crazy time.  Hopefully with that we can know we're not alone and help us better stay motivated to help our communities.  Below will be listed links for people to donate to and other resources.  Stay tuned and look forward to seeing you on thursday!

14:47 - Brandon Goodman Talks about White Guilt and Shame
20:35 - Reading Texts and Voicemails
29:38 - Trevor Noah on Rioting and Social Contracts
34:13 - Nina talks about telling her son about police brutality
41:46 - Reading Texts and Voicemails
48:23 - Preacher Lawson talks about Black Lives Matter
54:37 - More Texts and Voicemails
1:00:37 - Take Action
1:04:00 - What's going on (Cover)
1:07:30 - You've got a friend (Cover)
1:12:14 - Lean on me (Cover)
1:17:19 - Juicy (Cover)

DONATE TO
George Floyd Memorial Fund - https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd
Minnesota Freedom Fun - https://minnesotafreedomfund.org/
Reclaim the Block - https://www.reclaimtheblock.org/home
National Bail Out - https://secure.actblue.com/donate/freeblackmamas2020
Black Lives Matter - https://blacklivesmatter.com/
Campaign Zero - https://www.joincampaignzero.org/
National Bail Fund Network - https://www.communityjusticeexchange.org/nbfn-directory
The Innocent Project - https://www.innocenceproject.org/
Run With Maud - https://www.runwithmaud.com/
ACLU  - https://www.aclu.org/
NAACP Legal Defense Fund - https://www.naacpldf.org/

FOLLOW
@blklivesmatter
@colorofchange
@naacp
@civilrightsorg
@reclaimtheblock
@unitedwedream
@ethelsclub
@unitedwedrem
@showingupforracialjustice

REFLECT
-What can you to to support POC in your community?
-What are your local politicians’ policy on ending police brutality?
-When were you taught about race and culture?
-How do you plan on helping the fight to end racial discrimination and systematic oppression?
-How can you use anti-racist knowledge to change and progress conversations with friends, family, colleagues and peers?
-How can you be actively anti-racist instead of simply “not racist”?
-What do you want to learn more about?

TAKE ACTION
-Register to Vote
-Check in on your black friends, family, partners, and colleagues
-Learn what it means to be anti-racist
-Share and repost resources around you
-Don’t make the narrative around you, Identify privilege and condemn it.
-Continue the work when the outrage ends
-Continue to donate and support initiative you believe in if you can

BOOKS TO READ
-The Warmth of Other Suns: The Epic Story of America’s Great Migration by Isabel Wilkerson
-A Spectacular Secret: Lynching in American Life and Literature by Jacqueline Goldsby
-The New Jim Crow: Mass Incarceration in the Age of Colorblindness by Michelle Alexander
-So You Want to Talk About Race by Ijeoma Oluo
-Born a Crime: Stories from a South African Childhood by Trevor Noah
-How To Be An Antiracist by Ibram X. Kendi
-White Fragility by Robin DiAngelo
-Biased by Dr. Jennifer Eberhardt
-Wilmington’s Lie: The Murderous Coup of 1898 and the Rise of White Supremacy by David Zucchino
-Raising White Kids: Bringing Up Children In A Racially Unjust America by Jennifer Harvey
-Waking Up White by Debby Irving
-Citizen: An American Lyric by Claudia Rankine
-Brutal Imagination by Cornelius Eady

MOVIES TO WATCH
-The Hate U Give, a film based on the YA novel offering an intimate portrait of race in America
-Just Mercy, a film based on civil rights lawyer Bryan Stevenson’s work on death row in Alabama
-The 1965 debate between James Baldwin and William F. Buckley
-My hour on the history of Confederate statues in Nat Geo’s America Inside Out
-Becoming, a Netflix documentary following Michelle Obama on her book tour
-Let It Fall, a documentary looking at racial tensions in Los Angeles and the riots over Rodney King’s death
-When They See Us, a Netflix miniseries from Ava DuVernay about the Central Park Five
-13th, a Netflix documentary exposing racial inequality within the criminal justice system
-I Am Not Your Negro, a documentary envisioning the book James Baldwin was never able to finish
-Selma, a film that chronicles the marches of the Civil Rights Movement
-If Beale Street Could Talk


PROTESTING ETIQUETTE for non-POC
-Do Not Start Chants
-Some chants are not for you (I can't breathe, hands up don't shoot, *raising a fist in the air)
-Stop saying things need to be calm and peaceful, let POC dictate what tactics to employ
-Do not escalate things, but instead be willing to put yourself in the front and use your privilege to shield others from police
-Get off your phone, this is not the time to be posting, this is a time for solidarity, post later though but be weary of sharing peoples faces
-Don't talk to the press
-Dress appropriately with comfort in mind, you might be out there a whil


#blacklivesmatter
#icantbreathe
#saymyname
#morganjay
#livestream
#callinshow
#supportblacklives
#nojusticenopeace

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | THINGS THAT WHITE PEOPLE CAN DO TO HELP
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER | THINGS THAT WHITE PEOPLE CAN DO TO HELP
[Season 1, Episode 9]

Black Lives Matter

With the recent developments of the George Floyd murder, I think it is important to take action and start a conversation that a lot of white people are scared of and ultimately never start at all. Black lives matter, period. We have to do better. We have to start learning. I am inherently privileged because of the color of my skin, now reverse that and put yourself in the position that police brutality inherently has stemmed because of the color of someone-else's.

Enough is enough. I urge you to register to vote and make your voice heard. Every day I am learning something new I didn't know before. It hurts. It's painful. I am a good person and I want to do what's right but I have to learn what's wrong and what I'm doing wrong first to help solve it. Please help me by understanding and educating myself.

Next week I am going to be jumping on a zoom meeting with a couple of people to discuss racism and what are some things that white people can do to help. If you have questions or are feeling stuck and scared please comment below and I will do my very best to learn with you and direct the question or comment to someone that can help us learn together. 

I'm not doing this for clout or because I want people to think of me any sort of way other than the fact I want to learn, I want to grow, and I want to help. This is my starting point. #BLM

BLACK LIVES MATTER

REGISTER TO VOTE:

localized.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | THINGS THAT WHITE PEOPLE CAN DO TO HELP
localized.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER | THINGS THAT WHITE PEOPLE CAN DO TO HELP
[Season 1, Episode 9]

Black Lives Matter

With the recent developments of the George Floyd murder, I think it is important to take action and start a conversation that a lot of white people are scared of and ultimately never start at all. Black lives matter, period. We have to do better. We have to start learning. I am inherently privileged because of the color of my skin, now reverse that and put yourself in the position that police brutality inherently has stemmed because of the color of someone-else's.

Enough is enough. I urge you to register to vote and make your voice heard. Every day I am learning something new I didn't know before. It hurts. It's painful. I am a good person and I want to do what's right but I have to learn what's wrong and what I'm doing wrong first to help solve it. Please help me by understanding and educating myself.

Next week I am going to be jumping on a zoom meeting with a couple of people to discuss racism and what are some things that white people can do to help. If you have questions or are feeling stuck and scared please comment below and I will do my very best to learn with you and direct the question or comment to someone that can help us learn together. 

I'm not doing this for clout or because I want people to think of me any sort of way other than the fact I want to learn, I want to grow, and I want to help. This is my starting point. #BLM

snippet.title: These Hands of Change - Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Do not support me. This is not to promote myself- it is to use what abilities I have to try to support something greater. 

Support the movement. Support and listen to the voices of black people. Support the peaceful protesters who are being harmed and jailed. Support the lives lost by making their losses meaningful. Support community. Support change. Support a better future. 

Educate yourself. Spread awareness. Sign petitions. Contact your local officials. Donate. Watch videos and streams whose revenue will be donated in your place. Big or small, you can help make a change. Below are only a few options. Please research and choose what you want with your own breath. 

_ Sign Amnesty International's message to Minnesota Governor Tim Walz urging a clear message against excessive force by law enforcement upon minority persons, concerning the murder of George Floyd: 
https://www.amnesty.org/en/get-involved/take-action/george-floyd-police-violence-usa/ 

_ Join ColorofChange in texting "Floyd" to 55156 urging Mayor Jacob Frey that the officers involved in the murder of George Floyd are barred from becoming police officers again and do not receive related pensions: https://www.facebook.com/colorofchange/photos/a.10150403486291067/10158122764106067/?type=3&theater 

_ Watch Zoe Amira's video series fundraiser for BLM associated protester bail funds, featuring the content of black artists: 
https://youtu.be/bCgLa25fDHM 

_ Fund non-profit independent journalism covering criminal justice: 
https://www.themarshallproject.org/donate 

_ Take care of your holistic health to protect yourself against becoming overwhelmed and prevent compassion fatigue, and forgive yourself for your limits. Every mark matters, even the little ones. Do what you can. 

And remember- Protesters are protesting, looters are looting. Do not confuse them. Do not allow the juxtaposition in media to contaminate the message.

A man kicks away and rips down protest signs placed on a statue of Winston Churchill by anti-racism demonstrators on the second day of weekend rallies against George Floyd's death. Protesters defaced the monument of the former British Prime Minister, spray painting the words "was a racist" under his name.

snippet.title: ประท้วงใหญ่ต้านเหยียดสีผิวในอังกฤษ Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
การประท้วง Black Lives Matter ในสหราชอาณาจักร มีผู้เข้าร่วมชุมนุมจำนวนมาก แม้รัฐบาลจะขอให้อย่าออกไปชุมนุม เพราะสถานการณ์โควิด-19 แต่ผู้ชุมนุมต่างก็ออกมาเรียกร้องความเสมอภาค และความยุติธรรม 

คุณทศพล ชัยสัมฤทธิ์ผล นักศึกษาไทยในสหราชอาณาจักร รายงานสถานการณืการประท้วงใหญ่ต้านเหยียดสีผิว  Black Lives Matter ในสหราชอาณาจักร มีผู้เข้าร่วมชุมนุมจำนวนมากในเมืองคาร์ดิฟฟ์ แคว้นเวลส์
 
“เราต้องเสมอภาค เราต้องได้รับความยุติธรรม ชีวิตคนผิวดำก็มีความหมาย” ผู้ประท้วงคนหนึ่งกล่าวในเวทีชุมนุมต่อต้านการเหยียดสีผิวในเมืองคาร์ดิฟฟ์ สหราชอาณาจักร ที่มีผู้คนออกมาร่วมประท้วงนับพันคน แม้รัฐบาลจะขออย่าออกไปชุมนุม เพราะสถานการณ์โควิด-19 ยังไม่คลี่คลาย และไม่กี่วันก่อน ผู้เสียชีวิตทะลุ 4 หมื่นคนไปแล้ว
 
การประท้วง Black Lives Matter ถูกจุดชนวนขึ้นอีกครั้ง จากการใช้กำลังของตำรวจอเมริกันเพื่อจับกุม จอห์จ ฟลอยด์ ชายผิวดำในเมืองมินนีแอโปลิสของสหรัฐฯ เมื่อปลายเดือนที่แล้ว ซึ่งตอนนี้ การประท้วงต่อต้านการเหยียดสีผิวได้ลุกลามไปทั่วอเมริกา และหลายเมืองใหญ่ทั่วโลก

ติดตามรายงานจากคุณ ทศพล ชัยสัมฤทธิ์ผล

snippet.title: We've Had Enough (#BlackLivesMatter)
snippet.description:
I cannot pretend to know the extent of the struggle and pain endured by those who experience racism each day, but I do know the horror and anger I've felt witnessing the scenes of brutality and oppression we've all seen. Too many times.

Music is our shared language, and I hope that -- in some small way -- this song, with its heartbreaking and terribly timely words, might further highlight these stories of violence and injustice. We must be better than this. We must stand with those brave souls demanding justice. Because without justice, there can be no peace. 

WE'VE HAD ENOUGH
Song by Michael Jackson & Carole Bayer Sager

#BlackLivesMatter #BLM #NoJusticeNoPeace

snippet.title: "Not Enough" SuNWhoa Love #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
With a heavy heart, I wrote this song for me. 

In light of the last 400+ years, this video is for us. Every time I close my eyes and think about the many black lives snatched away too soon, their unlawful murders flash before my minds eye. The killing of Ahmaud Arbery and George Floyd most recently. The shooting of Philando Castile and Tamir Rice before that. The lifeless bodies of Sandra Bland, Eric Garner & Freddie Gray. These are only a few that come to mind. These traumatizing images seem to be engraved in my memory. God put it on my heart to show a different image. I pray this black girl magic doesn't distract you from the message, but this black girl magic is the message. I'm still trying to completely understand what it means to me metaphorically, but I know we need these images too.

We are a beautiful, resilient, and innovative people. Forced to double dutch through a country that doesn't love us. When we peacefully protest, you say that's not enough. When we fight wars, win gold medals, and create cultural standards, you still say that's not enough. What contributions must we make for you to deem our lives valuable enough to let us breathe. 

"I had to learn that hitting back with my fists one individual was not enough. It takes organization. It takes dedication. It takes the willingness to stand by and do what has to be done, when it has to be done." - Ella Josephine Baker

Love Y'all!
Thank you! 

-SuNWhoa

Written & Produced By SuNWhoa Love
Mixed By Kevin Randolph
Featuring video clips from "Black Magic" a Documentary by David Hoffman

snippet.title: WHO'S GEORGE? BLACK LIVES MATTER(GEORGE FLOYD( من هو جورج ؟ مسألة الحياة السوداء (جورج فلويد) (مترجم
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER

George Perry Floyd. (October 14, 1973 – May 25, 2020) was a 46-year-old African-American man who was born in Fayetteville, North Carolina, and raised in Houston, Texas. He attended Yates High School, where he played on the basketball and football teams. Floyd was a star tight end for Yates, helping them to the 1992 state championship final game. He attended South Florida Community College (now South Florida State College) from 1993 to 1995 and played on the school's basketball team. Floyd returned to Houston, where he joined the hip hop group Screwed Up Click and rapped under the stage name "Big Floyd", after entering the Houston Hip Hop cultural scene as an automotive customizer. In 2014, Floyd moved to Minnesota. He lived in St. Louis Park and worked in nearby Minneapolis as a restaurant security guard for five years, but lost his job due to Minnesota's stay-at-home order during the COVID-19 pandemic. Floyd was the father of two daughters, ages 6 and 22, who remained in Houston.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters are ‘destroying the COVID-19 social contract’
snippet.description:
Sky News host Sharri Markson says the Black Lives Matter protesters across Australia on Saturday could “very well be directly responsible” for a second wave of coronavirus cases.

Ms Markson said the “biggest worry” for the health officials and politicians throughout the country when deciding to lift restrictions was the risk of a second wave of the virus.

“It doesn’t matter what these protesters are protesting … the subject matter here is not relevant because these protesters are breaking the ban on mass gatherings, they’re risking their lives along with everyone else’s,” she said.

The protesters were quite clearly “breaking the ban” on mass gatherings, “flouting social compact” and were risking unravelling “all of the good work that we’ve done as a collective for the past 11 weeks”.

“I am disappointed and saddened and angry by the protesters who care so little for society, so little for our world, for our families, for our livelihoods, for our lives”.

“These protesters are destroying the social contract we’ve all made, to do our bit for the good of society.”

Image: News Corp Australia

snippet.title: Black Lives matter - George Floyd
snippet.description:
Black Life’s matter 

Together we can make a difference - 

WE ✊🏻 ARE ✊🏼 ALL ✊🏽 THE ✊🏾 SAME ✊🏿


If you are neutral in situations of injustice , you have chosen the side of the oppressor -Desmond Tutu 

Dedicated to George Floyd 🖤

Help me  God, I don’t want to die, 
please please please I’m not ready to say goodbye. 
I have every right to breath the same air, this is discrimination, please it isn’t fair. 
I no I’m black but I love my skin, 
he has no right to commit this gravely sin.

An innocent black man just died, strangulated on his side, 
handcuffed and pinned to the ground as witnesses gathered around 

Tears flowing down his face, treated badly due to his race  

The predudice, the discrimination, it is insane, imagine what he went through, 
imagine his pain
He starved him from oxygen, choking his neck, suffocating his brain 

Pinned to the ground , he lay gasping for air, the officer knew, but he didn’t care
His cries fell on deaf ears as his eyes swarmed with tears 

‘I can’t breathe’ he cried

Yet the officer felt he’s supreme, 
the pride on his face could be seen 
Thinkin he’s in control, 
effortlessly taking his soul, 

He wanted him dead, he wanted him killed, all because he could and willed. 

His soul left his body and his memories we now share, 
upset and baffled by the dispair

Together we can fight for justice, together we can make a stand.
Our voices need to be heard,
each and every word. 

Do it regardless of whether you’re brown, black or white, together let’s make things right

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: PROTESTS FOR GEORGE FLOYD: ST LOUIS, MO (Justice for George Floyd)
snippet.description:
PLEASE DO NOT START HATE IN THE COMMENTS!!! THIS IS ALL AN OPINION EDITORIAL PIECE! PEOPLE ARE ENTITLED TO THEIR OPINIONS. I personally do not condone violence, however I cannot blame people for acting out of anger after death of another human. We are all human. I made this video to address the recent events plaguing this country around POLICE BRUTALITY and the MURDERS of GEORGE FLOYD, AHMAUD ARBERY, BREONNA TAYLOR, and every other African American that has been affected by POLICE ABUSE OF POWER. I PROTESTED FOR GEORGE FLOYD IN ST LOUIS MO. I AM HERE TO SUPPORT BLACK LIVES MATTER.  PLEASE SUPPORT PROTESTS, MARCH, DONATE, SIGN PETITIONS, POST ABOUT THIS, SPREAD AWARENESS, SAY SOMETHING TO YOUR RACIST FRIENDS AND RELATIVES, CHECK ON BLACK FAMILY AND FRIENDS, EDUCATE YOURSELF!!! #BLM #MYSKINISNOTAWEAPON #JUSTICEFORGEORGEFLOYD

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Rally / March - Opening Statement - Bay City, Michigan (May 29, 2020)
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter (#BlackLivesMatter) march held in Bay City, Michigan the afternoon of Friday, May 29, 2020. It originated at Wenonah Park - on Friendship Plaza. Following some opening statements, the participants headed East along Center Avenue to the intersection of Washington Avenue. There, the group spread out to each of the four corners, with signs held out and rallying cries being shouted. Throughout the proceedings, there were no incidents - and it was a very peaceful, and insightful protest. This video is the opening statement by a friend, William Patrick Hystad, on Friendship Plaza. My apologies for the audio and shaky video. And, the labored breathing you can probably hear is me... This was the first time I'd actually worn a mask for any extended period of time, and the heat (along with my scampering around while grabbing photographs) was getting to me. Plus, my history of asthma and my habit of smoking didn't help, either.
Further information about this rally can be found in this article from MLive / The Bay City Times:
https://www.mlive.com/news/saginaw-bay-city/2020/05/minneapolis-demonstrations-spark-black-lives-matter-protest-in-downtown-bay-city-flint-mayor-statement.html .

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" - Spoken Word Poetry
snippet.description:
"A Beautiful Black Queen"

This piece is called “A Beautiful Black Queen…”
 Dedicated to ALL the BLACK LIVES that have been hurt, ruined and taken by YOU.

Let me tell you what it’s like to be me,
A beautiful ‘black.’ Queen.

But before I start, I know what you’re thinking…
Some of you look at me and see,
a supposed ‘light skin’ woman…
So, let me correct anyone who is blinded by my melanin,
Actually,
I am a beautiful BLACK QUEEN.

But to you, I am nothing but in between,
Black and white,
Love and lust,
Day and night.
Once again, to anyone blinded by my melanin…
I am a beautiful black queen.


And it isn’t fun and games,
Being me, 
in 2020.
In fact, it’s starting to become a tragedy…
Being a beautiful black queen.
In this time in history. 
Let me just address it simply;
All I want is to live peacefully
 and to be free.


And every day WE suffer!
From your narcistic and racial comments.
Treating us like we are inferior, 
When in fact, just admit, you fear our successes.
And see us as competition?

We are sometimes forced to wonder,
God why is this happening to US?
Do we not all bleed the same blood?
And breathe the same air? 


And yet we still hold our crowns up high every day.
Because we can’t allow such higher power,
strip that away,
Our crowns,
My crown. 
Not now.

Every day is a battle, for such coloured humans like me…
Thanks to YOU,
Purposely making it hard for us to be…
In this broken world.
Struggling to spread my wings,
And flourish as a beautiful black queen.


And of course, YOU will never understand,
What it’s like to spend every day,
living as a beautiful black queen.
Praying to God for protection.
From such oppressors,
From Such racists,
And,
From Such hatred.

Why are you so surprised when we make it?
These supremist preach equality,
But let’s be honest,
and open our eyes to finally S E E,
all the constant brutality,
and staged economy,
S E E,
This corrupt façade they created.


Now that I am awake to the world we live in;
And I can finally see,
 what I struggled to perceive,
When I was just a newborn baby.
I was blinded by white democracy,
And surrounded by flames of negativity.
All this…
Due to being a beautiful black queen.

Dear white people,
Haven’t you had enough?
Because every time I looked in the mirror,
I see peace and love…
whilst you, the oppressor, seen the opposite.
My name,
My skin colour,
And my religion.
So, you decided to start making my life tough.

Why do you perceive me as a threat?
Last time I checked,
I was a beautiful black queen.

And It’s starting to make sense now,
All the times I was left out,
And all the times I was bullied
ALL because of…
My skin,
My hair,
And,
My religion.
Spending years being misunderstood,
And pre-judged.
I admit it was a struggle growing up,
Being me,
A beautiful black queen.

Allah, protect my people…
Every day is a battle,
Being me,
A beautiful black queen.
Constantly fighting…
For my part,
For my voice,
To be heard,
And to be seen.

WE are alive, but we are not living.
Because if we starting living, 
They are out there patiently waiting,
To get rid of such beautiful black queens.

#BLACKLIVESMATTER

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter to God & to Us
snippet.description: George Floyd's death has impacted our multicultural church in NYC so deeply that we dedicated this Sunday discussion to the topic. Tears have flowed throughout our congregation, and brokenness and fears have been communicated. We are asking the question: WHAT DOES GOD HAVE TO SAY ABOUT RACISM? Interestingly, the Bible has so much to say — words of hope and encouragement, as well as warnings against the dangers of haughtiness. Jump in and get plugged into this discussion. We're praying for healing of hearts, reconciliation, and unity. Black lives matter so much to God, and we want the world to know they matter to all of us as well.

snippet.title: "The Colors of Our Skin" an original song. Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
I cannot not write a song about the state of the world right now and all of the hurt, the pain and the losses of many. Though I will never ever be able to understand the experiences of others, I WILL STAND WITH YOU AND FOR YOU to demand justice for George Floyd and many others. This song is called, "The Colors of Our Skin" and I really hope you guys can connect to it in some way, shape or form. Have those conversations, sign petitions, be proactive and spread love and life. We need to stand up and stand together. #Blacklivesmatter #RipGeorgeFloyd  
BUSINESS EMAIL: livreichley@gmail.com 

Lists of organizations to donate to: 
- Fair Fight: fairfight.com
- Equal Justice Initative: eji.org
- NAACP Legal Defense Fund: naacpldf.org
- Color of Change: colorofchange.org
- Bail Project: bailproject.org
- Campaign Zero: joincampaignzero.org
- Black Lives Matter: blacklivesmatter.com
- ACLU: aclu.org

Lyrics: 
The colors of our skin don't label who we are within, I feel so sad.
 The colors of our skin are predetermined whos to win, its just so bad. 
& the state that we are living, in a world thats just so cold. 
Now poeple all are dying & a good man just was choked. 
He's crying out for his mama, but all they saw was color. 
If we are all brothers & sisters why arent we treated equally? Equally.
 We're the colors of the rainbow we must stand with one another raise our voices & our hands until we are equally. 
Treated equally.

snippet.title: I Can't Breathe: Cellist Performs Dido's Lament for Black Lives Matter Protest
snippet.description:
NYC Cellist Yves Dhar performs a five-cello arrangement of "When I am laid in earth" (Dido's Lament) from Henry Purcell's Dido and Aeneas as a protest for Black Lives Matter and artistic tribute to George Floyd.

#icantbreathe
#BlackLivesMatter
#GeorgeFloyd 
#taketwoknees
#handsupdontshoot
#EnoughIsEnough

Recorded and produced entirely sheltered-in-place near Clearwater, FL after leaving New York City temporarily for the Covid-19 pandemic.  As an artist and longtime advocate dedicated to using music to inspire, to educate, and to make the world a better place, Yves Dhar (@yvesdhar) joins his friends and colleagues in Anthony McGill's #taketwoknees, a call-to-action for musicians to fight police brutality and systemic racism.

YouTube video footage courtesy of @antoniofonsecx, Eric Thomas, CBSN, WPLG Local 10, Sacramento Bee.

George Floyd mural in Minneapolis, MN created by Niko Alexander, Cadex Herrera, Greta McLain, Xena Goldman, Pablo Helm Hernandez.

snippet.title: Deputy involved shooting/ Black Lives Matter protest
snippet.description:
5/29/2020

An unarmed man was shot on Ave. K and 17th St. West in Lancaster, CA. The shooting took place around 7:48pm. A news release from the Sheriff's Information Bureau said:
“Deputies observed a suspect, male white adult, walking eastbound on the sidewalk. As deputies contacted the suspect they saw he had a firearm in his hand. An altercation with the suspect ensued and the suspect was taken to the ground, during which time a deputy-involved shooting occurred."
A replica firearm was found on scene.

Later, a Black Lives Matter protest took place and ended peacefully around 1:30am the following day.

http://theavtimes.com/2020/05/30/man-killed-in-deputy-involved-shooting-in-lancaster-demonstration-follows/

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MdP9inYPch0

Please like, share and subscribe for more independent, local news media!

snippet.title: பற்றி எரிகிறது அமெரிக்கா | George Floyd Death | Black lives matter #NoRacism
snippet.description:
The death of George Floyd, which triggered widespread protests across the US, has been declared a homicide in an official post-mortem examination.

The 46-year-old suffered a cardiac arrest while being restrained by Minneapolis police, the report found.

It listed Mr Floyd's cause of death as "cardiopulmonary arrest complicating law enforcement sub-dual, restraint, and neck compression".

A video showing a white police officer continuing to kneel on Mr Floyd's neck even after he pleaded he could not breathe has reignited deep-seated anger over police killings of black Americans.

For further details watch the video, The video has been explained in Tamil language but still the content could be understandable by any languages.

-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-

Listen Bro is the infotainment YouTube channel, which will try to provides you information in various range of exciting subjects!

If you like our videos watch, like, comment and share for your friends and do not forget to subscribe 😉


#GeorgeFloyd #BlackLivesMatter #NoRacism #Humanity

snippet.title: Black lives Matter #blk #justice
snippet.description: Being black is not a choice, being black is not easy, Being black isn’t the easy way out, being black is the harder road.. As a black male, I’ve been discriminated, I’ve seen my black brothers and sisters be discriminated, beat, Disrespected, hurt , sadly and wrongly killed. Being black is a hard obstacle that began when you born and you can’t change it or quit. We have to continue can do is fight! And March and let our voice be heard until we get Equality, before you discriminate against get to know me, before you judge me, listen to me. Justice will be serve but racism still exist... our fight is bigger then just justice with our cops.. help the world get to know the real you! Let’s start a movement together! #blacklivematter #BLK #justice#nojusticenopeace

snippet.title: Tribute to George Floyd #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
Little tribute made in memory of George Floyd. I wanted to mix the words of Dr. Martin Luther King on his 1963 speech "I HAVE A DREAM" with some rhythms I made specifically for the video.
Dr King said that : " 100 years later, the Negro still is not free" but sadly, 57 years after that speech, we realize the story didn't change

Lets go back to 1963 and take as ours the words of Dr. King. One Love. One Blood.



Pequeño homenaje hecho en memoria de George Floyd. Quería mezclar las palabras del Dr. Martin Luther King en su discurso de 1963 "TENGO UN SUEÑO" con algunos ritmos que hice específicamente para el video.
El Dr. King dijo que: "100 años después, el negro todavía no es libre", pero lamentablemente, 57 años después de ese discurso, nos damos cuenta de que la historia no cambió

Volvamos a 1963 y tomemos como nuestras las palabras del Dr. King. Un amor. Una sangre.

snippet.title: Driver ‘ploughs into George Floyd protester' at Black Lives Matter rally in Colorado
snippet.description:
A Driver was filmed speeding into George Floyd protestors in Denver on a third night of fury across America.

The driver of a vehicle ran over a protester during a George Floyd demonstration in Denver, Colorado.

Shocking video captured in Colorado appears to show a black Jeep Grand Cherokee plough into a group of protesters at a Black Lives Matter protest.

Protesters were rallying against the police-involved killing of black man George Floyd, in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

Footage from the Denver rally shows a driver speeding through a crowd of demonstrators before turning the car around and crashing into one of the protesters.

Protests, some violent, occurred across America since May 26, the day after video circulated of Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin pinning Floyd, 46, to the ground with his knee on his neck. Floyd died soon after, according to police.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter -  New Music and Video by Echoed Sycamore
snippet.description:
As an artist, I get most of my inspiration by daily events. After seeing recent events and tragedy that happened to George Floyd, I was not going to be able to stay silent so I have decided to express myself with the best way I can, through my music. These people have had enough! We need to do everything we can to put an end to racism. These reoccurring acts of racism are entirely unacceptable and are just cruel. Reacting to people practicing their rights should not be faced with violence, rather than listening and understanding so they can finally be heard. 

I am just an amateur when it comes to making videos. Most of the footage, I found from various documentaries and news channels from archives, and I edited them alongside of my original music. 

I hope this video serves a purpose. Maybe it gives new perspective and understanding for those who can not let hate and racism go. 

Video and Music by Echoed Sycamore/ Fatih B. Omeroglu

I am just an amateur when it comes to making videos. Most of the footage, I found from various documentaries and news channels from archives, and I edited them alongside of my original music. 

I hope this video serves a purpose. Maybe it gives new perspective and understanding for those who can not let hate and racism go. 

Video and Music by Echoed Sycamore/ Fatih B. Omeroglu

snippet.title: Black lives matter Demonstration in Fulda am 06.06.2020
snippet.description:
Nach dem gewaltsamen Tod des U.S. Bürgers George Floyd durch Polizeibeamte seiner Heimatstadt Minneapolis am 25.05.2020 gibt es seit Ende Mai, insbesondere in den Vereinigten Staaten von Amerika, aber auch weltweit Proteste gegen Rassismus und Polizeigewalt. Auch in Fulda haben am 06.06.2020 unter dem Motto der Black Lives Matter - Bewegung mehr als 2000 Menschen gegen Rassismus und rassistische Gewalt protestiert und damit ihre Solidarität mit den Demonstranten weltweit zum Ausdruck gebracht und auf das leider ebenfalls weltweite Problem Rassismus aufmerksam gemacht.
Die Demonstranten skandierten neben "black lives matter" auch "no justice, no peace" und "Stoppt den Rassismus" und zogen zunächst vom Universitätsplatz zum Platz Unterm Heilig Kreuz vor der Stadtpfarrkirche und später zum Bahnhofsplatz Fulda. Hier einige Impressionen.

snippet.title: #1 REASON WHY BLACK LIVES MATTER (MY STORY ON BEING RACIALLY  PROFILED BY THE POLICE)
snippet.description: The black community is hurting and we are all fed up by the injustice we experience daily. The murder of George Floyd and many others due to the effects of systemic racism constantly affects our mental wellbeing. We are tired of begging America to treat us as humans! We need solidarity and we need to share our individual experiences of racial profiling, police brutality, and the murdering of unarmed people of color at the hands of those sworn and paid to protect us.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
This is a tribute to George Floyd and every person of color who has been a victim of police brutality. There has to be a change made. To say “black lives matter” is not to say that other lives does not matter. It is the simple fact that for over 400 years, black and brown people have been oppressed and discriminated against because of their skin color. Our people are disproportionately killed/abused by people of power. Our lives matter. Any “all lives matter” comments in rebuttal to “black lives matter” will be deleted. 

Spoken word by Me. All rights belong to me.

snippet.title: in de VS roepen betogers 'Black Lives Matter', maar wat betekent dat precies?
snippet.description:
We hebben het deze week in Karrewiet heel vaak gehad over racisme en George Floyd. Dat is de zwarte man die werd gedood bij een politie-arrestatie. snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe


#BlackLivesMatter. Sign a petition. Make a donation. Get informed. Make a phone call. Do it all here: https://ellen.tv/2Azjfwb

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 


From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

Played by Arshia Jahanpour:
YOUTUBE: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC4an...
INSTAGRAM : https://www.instagram.com/arshiajahan...

snippet.title: 'Just the beginning': voices from the Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters gathered outside the US embassy in London on Sunday to show solidarity with demonstrators in America, where protests sparked by the police killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis continued into a second weekend. Crowds in the UK capital shouted slogans in support of the Black Lives Matter movement, calling for action to end racism and prejudice. 'There's so much more to be done,' said one protester, 'we still need to educate ourselves further.'

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter VS All Lives Matter (EXPLAINED)
snippet.description: Black Lives Matter or All Lives Matter? All lives can't matter until black lives matter. Saying black lives matter does not mean that ONLY black lives matter, it simply means black lives matter too. With the death of George Floyd and countless other black men at the hands of police and vigilantes, it is important to understand the difference between BLM and ALM. #BlackLivesMatter

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Crowds in Rome Kneel For 8 Minutes to Honor George Floyd
snippet.description:
Several hundred people protested peacefully in Rome's Piazza del Popolo to denounce the killing of George Floyd and show solidarity with anti-racism protests in the U.S. and elsewhere.

In English and Italian, protesters chanted "I can't breathe!" and kneeled for 8 minutes and 46 seconds, the amount of time George Floyd was pinned under a white police officer’s knee before he died.

snippet.title: Asians for Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
This vlog is for Black Lives Matter. Please take this time seriously. 
Special thanks to Kailyn Aaron-Lozano, Travis Giuse Nguyen and Erica Miley for their supports. We are very honored to work together to make this happen. 

[ID Description: A young light-skinned Asian-American male person with rounded square clear-framed glasses, black hair styled in an undercut, light goatee, and a brownish orange tshirt is signing in front of the camera. He is sitting in black chroma-based background.]

Transcript: 
What are we doing in our Asian community? We sit nothing allowing someone shot black person, so we can feel safe. Is this bystander called a safe? Why? This becomes repeating history. Should we find a way to avoid the same problem until our lives end? Our future generations facing the suffering of this same problem. Do something in action! Sign/Speak up for our POC community. 
Black people had been standing up for Asian community through racism. See what happen in COVID19 to us. This is horrible! After they supported us, we do nothing for them. 
Why again?
Please consider yourself and process your emotions/thoughts. 
If you aint Black Indigenous People of Color (BIPOC), please use your privilege to support our community. 
Look at polices. Look at doctors. Look at people. 
History today proves that the police violence is one of the top ten leading causes of death among Black people in America.  
Black people suffer their lives for many years.
Where are their safe and comfortable lives? 
Enough is still not enough for future. You can make this enough if you collaborate with us for our People of Color community. 
If they dont feel safe, we SHOULD feel safe, too. We can be next ones that will be targeted. 
Stand up and work together for Black community! 

#asiansforblacklivesmatter

This video is public and shareable. Voice Credit: Travis Giuse Nguyen.

snippet.title: June, 1 2020 (Black Lives Matter) - Logan Kendell
snippet.description:
#blackouttuesday #blacklivesmatter #resist #isupporttheprotests #antifa
This is what my anger and anxiety sound like.
Further context for history sake:
Following the murder of George Floyd by Police officers, which came on the heels of the murders of Ahmaud Arbery and Breonna Taylor, also by police officers, Black Lives Matter Protesters took to the streets around the world to protest Police Brutality and systemic racism. Most protests started peacefully, some devolved into rioting and looting, and some were stirred to violence by the police and White Nationalist agitators.

On June 1st, 2020, after calling protesters "Terrorists" and blaming "Antifa" for violence (side note, it has now been revealed that white nationalists in support of Trump created fake Antifa accounts to provoke violence that would support the presidents lies) Donald Trump sent military police to attack the peaceful protesters who had gathered outside the White House. Protesters and the press were attacked with tear gas, rubber bullets, pepper bombs, and more, and they were physically beaten with bats by police. This was done so Trump could take a photo holding a bible in front of the church accross the street from the white house. Ironically, a church Trump had never attended, he held the bible upside down in the photo, and among those driven from the property by his stormtroopers were the leadership of the church itself who had set up a table to give aid to the protesters. The public joined together for "Black Out Tuesday" as a simple way to show support for the Black Lives Matter movement.
I composed this piece to underscore my rage towards the president, the alllivesmatter movement and all their racist supporters, the police, and the broken state of the USA.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest in Baldwin
snippet.description:
I’m so unbelievably proud to call Baldwin my hometown. The turnout for the BLM protest was more than I’d ever imagined, and it was beautiful to see so many people, regardless of color, care about a single marginalized group. I’ve never really thought about race, and that privilege was given to me by growing up in a diverse environment, and it’s a shame to see so much ignorance in people who weren’t as lucky. This beautiful poem was written by 15 year old Baldwin student, Jaylynn Valentin.

Jaylynn's Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/jaylynn_valentin/

snippet.title: Thousands attend Black Lives Matter protest at US embassy in Dublin
snippet.description:
Over 3,000 people held a Black Lives Matter demonstration outside the US embassy in Dublin today.

While they defied the advice of Chief Medical Officer Tony Holohan and Lord Mayor Brabazon to call off the protest on public health grounds, the majority of those who attended wore face masks.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: The Stats, History, and ISSUES with Police Brutality
snippet.description: The phrase "I can't breathe" encircles 6 years during which we have been reminded time and again that Black people are not safe in North America. It's been 7 years since the Black Lives Matter movement began. Likely, it will continue to be mere days since the most recent case of Police homicide against a person of color. This has to stop. In this video, I speak about stats on police brutality, and 4 key issues I have found through research that maintain our current police homicide epidemic - from implicit bias to the Police Academy's military structure. We have to be loud, continue this conversation long after it stops trending, and we can't stop this fight until all police know that #BLACKLIVESMATTER

snippet.title: Fleur East's Black Lives Matter Rap Roulette Is Incredibly Powerful | Hits Radio
snippet.description:
Hits Radio Breakfast's Fleur East's Rap Roulette was about Black Lives Matter. Her lyrics are incredibly powerful, read the lyrics below.
 
Black lives matter that’s the message that’s the fight, the fight against racism and not against white / It’s a movement with a message that is centuries old, so if you stand against injustice then speak up and be bold 

We’ve seen everybody come together, stay at home and work together fighting against a virus that we can’t even see / Now we face another virus one called racism, and silence isn't gonna save lives or protect you and me. 

8 minutes 46 seconds can you believe?! / George Floyd was held down saying he couldn’t breathe 

It’s time to stand up. Time to put your hands up. Time to understand love’s the answer and enough is enough / People fear for their lives through the shade they were painted / Can you see the picture has been tainted? 

The hashtag does not accuse you or exclude you, saying all lives matter is only seeing what you choose to, if you don’t have a clue it’s like crashing a stranger's funeral and screaming ‘yeah I lost someone too!’

The inequality, complexity, the pain and the perplexity / The gunning and running and shunning and numbing the pain, the sheer immensity 

We’re meant to be in this together so speak up for your brothers for your sisters, sons and daughters for the slaughtered 

Born to a black mother and my father was white / My future children will be black and we’ll continue the fight 

Do something, say something yeah, we all have a voice / And in the colour of our skin, none of us had a choice / You can continue to divide, but the truth will remain / Underneath our skin we all bleed the same’

snippet.title: God Bless The Child #blacklivesmatter #blm
snippet.description:
“God Bless The Child” 
Recorded in New York City on June 1, 2020. 
Lyrics and Music: Billie Holiday / Arthur Herzog Jr.  // Vocals, Guitar: EV @etherealvarnish 
Images compiled & hastily edited by EV

On the eve before the music industry black out I must take this moment to honor the black community. The woman who originally wrote this song fought her entire life and sung her entire life for equality and fought against the injustices inflicted upon her community & upon her. Her music and her fight transcended the decades prior to and since her passing in 1959. Her fight and her words and her voice along with the words and voices of so many other artists & activists have inspired generation after generation to stand up and join the fight for equality. 

Billie Holiday wrote this song in 1939 and I am proud to sing it today and be part of such a noble and long-overdue fight! I kneel beside you, my brothers and sisters of the black community and I hold my head and chest so so high with pride and hope, today and forever, as I kneel and pray. 

I want to make it known that, this is not about me, as a white man, but I need to thank you. Thank you for you helped me find my soul and my higher power through your music. 50's and 60's rock n' roll, jazz, tribal, disco, the influence that the black community has had on music and on me is INFINITE and I'm just so fucking honored and grateful and proud to stand here beside you my friends. #BlackLivesMatter

From My Soul, I love you.

-EV 
6-1-2020

I’m sorry to all the black families out there that have to deal with this problem and I’m sorry that I will never truly know your struggles you have to go through! But, one thing I do know is that black people are human too! Did they have a choice of being born that color? No! So why does the color of their skin make them any different from the rest of us, they are humans living in this earth except having to worry about cops attacking them JUST because of their SKIN COLOR?!

snippet.title: If the World Was Ending  - Black Lives Matter version - montage
snippet.description:
This is a montage I made using “If the World Was Ending” cover Black Lives Matter version written and performed by Alonzo (and posted on his Tik Tok). After I heard it, I wanted to put something together for it. Please like, comment, and share! Thanks!

SONG: If the World Was Ending cover (Black Lives Matter edition)
WRITTEN AND PERFORMED BY: Alonzo

~*~

Videos I used for the montage: 

"I CAN'T BREATHE:" Black Lives Matter protests after George Floyd's death in Minneapolis - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5pN-btn7nUw

A History of the Black Lives Matter Movement - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jMedqlxbFfM

Protesters gather in NYC to demand racial justice after Ahmaud Arbery's death - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jHxrDpeU3pY

BET’s Award-Winning The Truth Series Returns ... - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FooSiTbImXk

~*~

I started a "fan page" for my montages on facebook. Please take a look and "LIKE!"

https://www.facebook.com/montagemadebyjackiev
